  "Monument": "Maarjam√§e Palace",
  "Short": "Maarjam√§e Palace in Tallinn, Estonia, has a rich history that spans centuries. Initially known as Strietberg, it was a popular summer destination. Over time, it housed a sugar factory and later became a summer manor. In the 1930s, it was transformed into an elegant restaurant-hotel called Riviera-Palais. During various periods, the palace served as a military aviation school and Soviet Army quarters. Extensive renovations took place in the 1980s, restoring the palace's external appearance and creating exhibition spaces. Today, Maarjam√§e Palace is part of the Estonian History Museum and serves as a history discovery center. Visitors can explore the interactive exhibition  My Free Country,  which chronicles Estonia's past and future. The palace is also home to the Estonian Film Museum, and the surrounding park offers recreational areas and outdoor exhibitions.",
  "Medium": "Maarjamae Palace, located in Tallinn, Estonia, has a fascinating history that reflects the changing times and uses of the site. Originally called Strietberg, it was a sought-after spot for summer leisure activities. In the late 17th century, a small summer manor was established there by Christian von Geldern, a councillor and member of the Brotherhood of Blackheads. Over the years, the site underwent various transformations. In 1811, a sugar factory was built on the premises by Johan Gottlieb Clementz, giving rise to the local name  Suhkrum√§gi  (Sugar Hill). By the 1820s, Tallinn had become a renowned beach resort, attracting visitors to the area. In 1861, Christian Abraham Rotermann, a councillor and entrepreneur, acquired the site and repurposed it as a starch and spirit factory. However, a devastating fire in 1869 brought an end to the factory operations. In 1873, the property changed hands once again, this time purchased by Count Anatoli Orlov-Davydov. He named the place Marienberg, later known as Maarjam√§e, after his wife, Maria. Over time, the Orlov-Davydov family emigrated, and the summer manor was leased. In 1933, Maarjam√§e Palace took on a new role as the grand opening of the Riviera-Palais restaurant-hotel attracted attention. With its elegant atmosphere and scenic surroundings, it became a popular destination for grand receptions and festive events. However, in 1937, the palace was purchased by the government, leading to its transformation into the Military Aviation School of the Republic of Estonia. Throughout the years, Maarjam√§e Palace endured a tumultuous history, serving as Soviet Army quarters and falling into disrepair. However, in the 1980s, extensive restoration works took place, reviving the palace's external appearance and creating exhibition spaces suitable for the Estonian History Museum's needs. Today, Maarjam√§e Palace stands as a history discovery center, offering visitors the opportunity to engage with Estonia's past and future. The exhibition  My Free Country,  unveiled on the 100th anniversary of the Republic of Estonia, guides visitors through the nation's history over the past century. The palace also houses the Estonian Film Museum, providing insights into the country's cinematic heritage. The surrounding park offers pleasant recreational areas and engaging outdoor exhibitions, making Maarjam√§e Palace a captivating destination for history enthusiasts and families alike.",
  "Long": "Maarjam√§e Palace, situated in Tallinn, Estonia, holds a remarkable history that reflects the transformation and uses of the site over the centuries. Originally known as Strietberg, it served as a popular summer retreat where people sought respite during the warm months. In the late 17th century, Christian von Geldern, a councillor and member of the Brotherhood of Blackheads, established a small summer manor on the site. In 1811, Johan Gottlieb Clementz, a merchant, purchased a plot of land at Strietberg and erected a sugar factory, leading locals to refer to the area as Suhkrum√§gi (Sugar Hill). By 1820, in addition to the factory building, there were eleven other stone structures, a wooden dwelling, sheds, a smithy, a lime kiln, an arched ice cellar, and a pool with canals used to direct water to the factory. The area was enclosed by a limestone wall standing over 4 meters high, and several of the stone buildings, the ice cellar, and parts of the perimeter wall have been preserved. In 1861, Christian Abraham Rotermann, a councillor and founder of a storeyard, acquired the sugar factory. He converted the premises into a starch and spirit factory, making significant contributions to Tallinn's industrial landscape. However, a devastating fire in 1869 destroyed the factory, leading Rotermann to cease operations at Strietberg. By the 1820s, Tallinn had gained renown as a beach resort, attracting visitors from near and far. On January 29, 1873, Count Anatoli Orlov-Davydov, a resident of St. Petersburg, acquired the Strietberg property and its buildings from Rotermann's heirs. The count named the place Marienberg, possibly in honor of his wife, Maria. The Estonian version of the name, Maarjam√§e, gained popularity in the late 1930s. With the Orlov-Davydov family's emigration following the 1917 revolution, the summer manor was leased to various occupants. In 1933, Maarjam√§e Palace underwent another transformation when it became the Riviera-Palais, an elegant restaurant-hotel that quickly became a renowned venue for grand receptions, literary and musical events, and Midsummer's Eve celebrations. Warm fireplaces, an illuminated glass dance floor, and scenic surroundings added to its allure. However, in 1937, the palace was acquired by the government, leading to its conversion into the Military Aviation School of the Republic of Estonia. The school welcomed its first students on November 1, 1937, and its mission was to train military pilots, reconnaissance pilots, and aircraft technicians. Reconstruction works were carried out, including the demolition of the veranda and balcony, altering the fa√ßade's appearance. In 1940, Maarjam√§e Palace came under the control of the Soviet Army. After the army vacated the premises, the palace was filled with apartments and communal kitchens. The once-neat and tidy area fell into disrepair and ruins. In the 1980s, restoration efforts took place to revive the palace and its historical significance. Restorers from the Wroclav department of the Polish company PKZ worked on the first stage of the palace complex from 1983 to 1988. The external appearance of the buildings, including the grand staircase, was meticulously restored based on old photographs and drawings. However, the interior was reconfigured to accommodate the needs of the museum. An annex was also constructed, featuring a two-story cinema hall adorned with bronze sculptures by Ants M√∂lder. Evald Okas created a mural titled  Friendship of Nations  in 1987 for the former summer hall of the palace, aligning with the prevailing zeitgeist. The palace connected to a Classicist auxiliary building from the first half of the 19th century, which now served as workrooms. In late 1987, the History and Revolution Museum of the Estonian SSR opened in the palace, presenting Estonian history from the mid-19th century to the modern era. It was the last permanent exhibition in Estonia subject to direct orders from the ideologists of the Estonian Communist Party's Central Committee. Following the restoration of Estonia's independence, the permanent exhibition was updated to reflect the country's new era. The auxiliary buildings on the slopes of Maarjam√§e were renovated and repurposed as museum depositories. The entire area continues to undergo general cleaning and landscaping. In 2008, the first-floor permanent exhibition was further updated, coinciding with the opening of the grand exhibition  Will to be free. 90 Years of the Republic of Estonia  commemorating the nation's 90th anniversary. On the 100th anniversary of the Republic of Estonia, Maarjam√§e Palace, as part of the Estonian History Museum, was unveiled as a history discovery center. The palace underwent renovations, and the Estonian Film Museum found its home in the surrounding park. Visitors can explore the exhibition  My Free Country,  which unfolds over 100 years, offering insights into Estonia's past and fostering discussions about its future. Additionally, children can engage in building their own country within the enjoyable Children's Republic. Maarjam√§e Palace stands as a testament to Estonia's rich history and cultural heritage. It serves as a hub for historical exploration, exhibitions, and educational programs, inviting both locals and visitors to delve into the nation's past and envision its future.",
