  "Monument": "Tallin Great Guild Hall",
  "Short": "The Great Guild Hall in Tallinn is a notable medieval public building. Completed in 1410, this Gothic-style structure was commissioned by the Great Guild, an association of Hanseatic merchants. Throughout history, it has hosted a wide range of events, from lavish parties to church services and court proceedings. In the Middle Ages, the cellar stored wine, and in the 19th and 20th centuries, it operated as a popular wine cellar called  Das S√ºsse Loch  ( Sweet Hole ). Since 1952, the Estonian History Museum has been located in the Great Guild Hall. In 2010-2011, the building underwent extensive restoration and refurbishment, supported by the European Regional Development Fund and the Estonian Ministry of Culture. The interior design and new permanent exhibition were collaborative efforts involving the Estonian History Museum, O√ú KOKO Arhitektid, and O√ú Produktsioonigrupp. The Great Guild Hall holds significant historical importance as it reflects the trade and cultural developments of medieval northern Europe. In recognition of its significance, it was awarded the European Heritage Label in 2013.",
  "Medium": "The Great Guild Hall in Tallinn stands as an iconic medieval public building. Its Gothic-style architecture, completed in 1410, bears witness to the historical importance of the Great Guild, an association of Hanseatic merchants who played a pivotal role in the city's commerce and culture. Throughout the centuries, the Great Guild Hall served as a versatile venue, hosting a wide range of events such as grand parties, religious services, and legal proceedings. In medieval times, the cellar was a storeroom for wine, while the 19th and 20th centuries saw the rise of the popular wine cellar known as  Das S√ºsse Loch  or  Sweet Hole.  Since 1952, the Estonian History Museum has found its home within the walls of the Great Guild Hall, offering visitors insights into the nation's rich heritage. In 2010-2011, a comprehensive restoration and refurbishment project took place, generously supported by the European Regional Development Fund and the Estonian Ministry of Culture. Collaborating with O√ú KOKO Arhitektid and O√ú Produktsioonigrupp, the Estonian History Museum crafted an immersive interior design and a new permanent exhibition. The Great Guild Hall's historical significance extends beyond Tallinn, as it represents the trade and cultural developments that shaped medieval northern Europe. Recognizing its importance, the European Heritage Label was bestowed upon it in 2013.",
  "Long": "The Great Guild Hall in Tallinn stands as one of the most distinguished public buildings from the medieval era. Completed in 1410, this remarkable example of Gothic architecture holds a significant place in the city's history. It was commissioned by the Great Guild, an association of Hanseatic merchants who played a vital role in Tallinn's trade and economy. Situated on what was once the main street, in proximity to the Town Hall, the Great Guild Hall has witnessed centuries of important events. From grand parties to religious services and court proceedings, it has been a central hub of activity. In its early years, the cellar of the Great Guild Hall served as a storage space for wine, reflecting the significance of trade and the role of merchants in medieval Tallinn. In the 19th and 20th centuries, the building underwent transformations, including its famous wine cellar known as  Das S√ºsse Loch  or  Sweet Hole,  which attracted locals and visitors alike. During this period, the Great Guild Hall was not only a place of business but also a vibrant arts venue, adding to its cultural significance.Since 1952, the Estonian History Museum has found its home within the Great Guild Hall. This institution preserves and presents the rich heritage of Estonia, making the historical building an ideal setting for showcasing the nation's past. In recognition of its historical and cultural importance, the Great Guild Hall underwent thorough restoration and refurbishment between 2010 and 2011. This ambitious project was made possible with funding from the European Regional Development Fund and the Estonian Ministry of Culture, with the support of Enterprise Estonia. The interior design and the creation of a new permanent exhibition were collaborative endeavors involving the Estonian History Museum, O√ú KOKO Arhitektid, and O√ú Produktsioonigrupp. The architectural design was carried out by O√ú Restor, with construction work handled by O√ú Tarrest Ehitus. The history of the Great Guild Hall is closely intertwined with the trade and cultural developments of medieval northern Europe. The Great Guild, as the most influential organization in Tallinn for centuries, played a pivotal role in shaping the city's commercial landscape. Its interactions with the Hanseatic League offer a fascinating glimpse into the story of European  integration  during medieval times. In recognition of its historical significance and architectural value, the Great Guild Hall was honored with the European Heritage Label in 2013. Today, the Great Guild Hall stands as a testament to Tallinn's rich history and cultural heritage. It serves as a venue for the Estonian History Museum, inviting visitors to explore and immerse themselves in the captivating narrative of Estonia's past. The Great Guild Hall's grandeur and architectural beauty make it a captivating destination for locals and tourists alike. The restoration and refurbishment project undertaken between 2010 and 2011 aimed to preserve the historical integrity of the Great Guild Hall while providing modern amenities and a renewed exhibition space. The European Regional Development Fund and the Estonian Ministry of Culture played a crucial role in supporting the construction work and the development of the new permanent exhibition. The collaborative efforts of the Estonian History Museum, O√ú KOKO Arhitektid, O√ú Produktsioonigrupp, O√ú Restor, and O√ú Tarrest Ehitus ensured the successful completion of the project. Visitors to the Great Guild Hall can now delve into the rich history of the Hanseatic merchants and the role they played in Tallinn's prosperity. The exhibition spaces offer engaging displays, interactive elements, and informative narratives that shed light on various aspects of medieval trade, culture, and society. From the bustling trading activities to the grand celebrations that took place within its walls, the Great Guild Hall brings the past to life. The significance of the Great Guild Hall extends beyond Tallinn's borders. In 2013, it was honored with the prestigious European Heritage Label, recognizing its importance as a cultural heritage site that represents the trade and cultural developments of medieval northern Europe. This accolade further solidifies the Great Guild Hall's status as a must-visit destination for those seeking to uncover the captivating stories of the past. As visitors explore the halls, chambers, and exhibitions of the Great Guild Hall, they can gain a deeper understanding of Tallinn's rich history, appreciate the architectural splendor of the medieval era, and gain insights into the lives and achievements of the Hanseatic merchants who shaped the city's destiny. The Great Guild Hall stands as a testament to the enduring legacy of the past and invites all who enter to embark on a captivating journey through time.",
