  "Monument": "Danish King's Garden",
  "Short": "The Danish King's Garden is a green area in Tallinn's Old Town, located west of R√º√ºtli Street. It is named after the Danish king Valdemar II, whose victory in 1219 led to Danish rule in Tallinn for over a hundred years. Legends suggest that the Danish flag, Dannebrog, was obtained by the Danes in this very place during a battle on Toompea Hill. The garden is adorned with a stone memorial plaque dedicated to artists Paul and Kristjan Raua. It serves as a serene retreat and hosts the annual Dannebrog Day celebration, commemorating the historic ties between Denmark and Estonia.",
  "Medium": "The Danish King's Garden, situated in Tallinn's Old Town west of R√º√ºtli Street, holds a special place in the city's history. Named after King Valdemar II, whose victory in 1219 established Danish rule in Tallinn, the garden is surrounded by intriguing legends. According to one tale, the Danish forces received their sacred flag, Dannebrog, on the slopes of Toompea Hill, where they bravely repelled their opponents. The garden features a stone memorial plaque dedicated to the renowned artists Paul and Kristjan Raua, who contributed their talent while working in the nearby Maiden Tower. In the 14th century, the Danish King Erik Menved played a significant role in the garden's history by resolving a dispute between Tallinn's sub-city and the rulers of Estonia. With the king's permission, merchants and craftsmen were allowed to continue their activities in the area. This grant bestowed upon the city a cherished freedom‚Äîto utilize the designated territory on Toompea Mountain without hindrance. Today, the Danish King's Garden serves as an idyllic retreat within the bustling Old Town. Its lush greenery and serene ambiance provide a peaceful setting for locals and visitors alike. Each year, Dannebrog Day is celebrated in the garden, honoring the historic connection between Denmark and Estonia.",
  "Long": "The Danish King's Garden, located in Tallinn's Old Town west of R√º√ºtli Street, holds a significant place in the city's history and folklore. The garden derives its name from King Valdemar II, whose victorious campaign in 1219 established Danish rule in Tallinn and Northern Estonia for over a hundred years. According to legend, the Danes obtained their national flag, Dannebrog, at the very spot where the garden now stands. During a battle on the slopes of Toompea Hill, the Estonian malev (militia) attacked the Danish camp. In his desperate prayer for divine assistance, King Valdemar witnessed a miraculous event as a red flag with a white cross descended from the sky. Inspired by this celestial intervention, the Danish forces were able to repel their opponents and secure victory. In the 14th century, the garden earned its name   Garden of the Danish King   due to the gratitude of Tallinn's citizens. This recognition came in response to King Erik Menved's resolution of a dispute that arose during the planning of the Tallinn city wall. The king confirmed the construction line of the city wall, protecting Toompea and the lower city, thereby granting the merchants and craftsmen of Tallinn's sub-city the right to continue their activities in the area. This privilege bestowed upon the city-state the enduring right to utilize the slope of Toompea Mountain, ensuring that   no one was ever allowed to prevent or disturb   the people of Tallinn from exercising their freedom within this territory. The Danish King's Garden serves as a tranquil oasis within the historic Old Town. Amidst its verdant surroundings, the garden features a stone memorial plaque dedicated to the esteemed artists Paul and Kristjan Raua. Their contribution to the cultural heritage of Tallinn is commemorated in this serene setting. Visitors can appreciate the picturesque landscape while contemplating the city's rich artistic traditions. One of the garden's notable features is the annual celebration of Dannebrog Day, which honors the historic connection between Denmark and Estonia. This special day commemorates the Danish flag, symbolizing the enduring ties between the two nations. It is an occasion for reflection and appreciation of the shared history and cultural exchange between Denmark and Estonia. The Danish King's Garden invites locals and tourists alike to bask in its serene atmosphere and absorb the profound historical significance of the site. Amidst the whispers of legends and the timeless beauty of the surroundings, visitors can find solace and a deeper understanding of the intertwined destinies of Estonia and Denmark.",
