  "Monument": "Saint Nicolas Church and Museum",
  "Short": "St. Nicholas‚Äô Church, founded in the 13th century, was a prominent parish church in medieval Tallinn. Dedicated to St. Nicholas, the patron saint of merchants and seafarers, it was known for its wealth. The church underwent various expansions and renovations over the centuries, including the addition of chapels and the rebuilding of the chancel and nave. St. Nicholas‚Äô Church housed numerous side altars and valuable works of art, such as Bernt Notke‚Äôs Dance of Death and the magnificent retable of the high altar from the workshop of Hermen Rode. With the arrival of the Reformation, the church became a Lutheran congregation and underwent further modifications to accommodate the new faith. Epitaphs and memorial chapels were added to honor notable individuals. The Chapel of St. George was eventually transformed into the North Hall.",
  "Medium": "St. Nicholas‚Äô Church, founded in the mid-13th century, played a significant role as one of the two parish churches in medieval Tallinn. Over the years, the church underwent several expansions and reconstructions. In the 14th century, chapels, including St. George's Chapel and the Small Chapel, were added to the northern side of the church. A more comprehensive rebuilding took place in the 15th century, resulting in the current appearance of the chancel and nave. During this time, St. Matthew's Chapel was fully rebuilt, becoming a spacious room with a groined vault. St. Nicholas' Church flourished during the Hanseatic era and housed numerous side altars and valuable works of art commissioned from renowned European centers. Notable pieces include Bernt Notke's Dance of Death and Hermen Rode's magnificent retable of the high altar. In the 16th century, the church embraced the Reformation and became a Lutheran congregation. Changes were made to accommodate the new faith, including the installation of pews and a pulpit with intricate depictions of biblical scenes. Memorial chapels and epitaphs were added to honor prominent individuals buried in the church, and the Chapel of St. George was transformed into the North Hall.",
  "Long": "St. Nicholas' Church, founded in the middle of the 13th century, stands as a testament to Tallinn's rich medieval history. Over the centuries, the church has witnessed numerous transformations and played a prominent role in the city's religious and cultural life. The construction of the church began with the square-shaped 13th-century chancel, which still lies beneath the present structure. As the church grew in importance and influence, additional elements were added, including a three-aisled nave, a sacristy, and the lower part of the western tower. In the 15th century, a significant rebuilding project was undertaken, resulting in the current appearance of the chancel and nave. A new chancel was established on the site of the old one, featuring a polygonal apse and an ambulatory. The walls of the church aisles were heightened, and the church was transformed into a basilica. Notable additions during this period include the complete reconstruction of St. Matthew's Chapel, renamed St. Anthony's Chapel, which featured a spacious room with a groined vault. During the Middle Ages, St. Nicholas' Church was renowned for its magnificence and beauty. It housed over 20 side altars and became a showcase for the prosperity and artistic patronage of the local merchants. Remarkable works of art, such as Bernt Notke's Dance of Death and Hermen Rode's exquisite retable of the high altar, adorned the church, demonstrating the craftsmanship of L√ºbeck masters from the Late Middle Ages. Among the church's treasures was a remarkable seven-armed brass candelabrum, one of the largest of its kind in the world. With the advent of the Reformation in the 16th century, St. Nicholas' Church underwent significant changes. It became a Lutheran congregation church, and Renaissance-style pews were added for the congregation, adorned with a pictorial program depicting biblical characters. The church's interior was further enhanced with balconies and an exquisite pulpit that depicted scenes from the life of Christ. Epitaphs and coat-of-arms epitaphs were installed on the walls to commemorate notable individuals buried within the church. In subsequent centuries, memorial chapels dedicated to prominent figures were erected, including those of Bogislaus von Rosen, Gustav Adolf Clodt, and Peter August von Holstein-Beck. The Chapel of St. George eventually underwent transformation into the North Hall, serving as a versatile space within the church. Today, St. Nicholas' Church stands as a remarkable testament to Tallinn's rich architectural and artistic heritage. Its grandeur, historical significance, and impressive collection of artworks continue to attract visitors from around the world, allowing them to experience the vibrant history and cultural legacy of this iconic medieval church.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tallinn/Saint%20Nicolas%20Church%20and%20Museum.jpg"
 },
