  "Monument": "Estonian Knighthood House",
  "Short": "The Estonian Knighthood House, located in Toompea, Tallinn's historic inner town, is a notable building with a rich history. It served as the meeting place for the German nobles of the Estonian Knighthood, who held power in Estonia for centuries. The current Renaissance Revival-style building, designed by architect Georg Winterhalter and constructed between 1845 and 1848, is the fourth Knighthood House. After Estonia gained independence in 1920, the building was repurposed as the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. It later served as the National Library of Estonia from 1948 to 1992. In 1993, part of the art collection from Kadriorg Palace found a home in the Estonian Knighthood House. Today, the building houses the Estonian Academy of Arts, although it is slated to relocate in 2016.",
  "Medium": "Situated in the picturesque Toompea district of Tallinn, the Estonian Knighthood House stands as a testament to the influence and legacy of the German nobles in Estonia. Throughout history, these nobles played a significant role in governing the region, and the Knighthood House served as their esteemed meeting place. The current building, a remarkable example of Renaissance Revival architecture, was designed by the renowned architect Georg Winterhalter and constructed between 1845 and 1848. In the aftermath of Estonia's independence in 1920, the Knighthood House witnessed a transformation as it became the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, symbolizing the nation's pursuit of diplomatic endeavors on the international stage. However, the turbulent times of occupation saw the building's purpose evolve once again. From 1948 to 1992, it housed the National Library of Estonia, providing a haven for knowledge and intellectual pursuits. In a significant cultural move, the Estonian Knighthood House became a sanctuary for art in 1993. A portion of the esteemed art collection from Kadriorg Palace found a new home within its walls, temporarily enriching its historical ambiance with creative expression. As the years unfolded, the art collection gradually returned to its original location, making way for the restored Kadriorg Palace and the magnificent Kumu Art Museum. Today, the Estonian Knighthood House is proudly home to the Estonian Academy of Arts. It serves as a hub for creative exploration and academic excellence, nurturing the talents and aspirations of future artists and designers. However, change is on the horizon, as the Estonian Academy of Arts is set to move into a meticulously reconstructed historical factory building in the vibrant Kalamaja quarter in 2016. This move signifies the continuous growth and evolution of Estonia's artistic landscape.",
  "Long": "Nestled within the enchanting Toompea district of Tallinn, the Estonian Knighthood House stands as an architectural gem with a compelling historical narrative. Since the 13th century, when Estonia was under the rule of the Livonian Brothers of the Sword, German nobles assumed positions of power and influence in the region. As these nobles united under the Estonian Knighthood, the Knighthood House became their cherished gathering place, where celebrations and meetings were held and their esteemed peerage register was meticulously maintained. The current iteration of the Knighthood House, an exquisite embodiment of Renaissance Revival style, emerged through the vision of architect Georg Winterhalter and the craftsmanship of skilled builders between 1845 and 1848. It replaced its predecessors, which were lost to fires or outgrown by the burgeoning needs of the Knighthood. The winds of change swept through Estonia in 1920, as the nation gained independence and the privileges of the German Knights were revoked. The Knighthood House found a new purpose as it became Estonia's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, symbolizing the country's diplomatic aspirations on the global stage. However, the course of history took another turn with the Soviet occupation of Estonia in 1940. The nation's Ministry of Foreign Affairs ceased to exist, and the Knighthood House underwent a transformation yet again. From 1948 to 1992, it served as the National Library of Estonia, preserving and disseminating knowledge to generations of eager minds. During this time, the building became a sanctuary of learning, nurturing intellectual curiosity and fostering a sense of cultural heritage. In 1993, the Knighthood House embarked on a new chapter, welcoming a part of the esteemed art collection from Kadriorg Palace. This infusion of artistic expression breathed new life into the building's storied halls, providing a space for contemplation and appreciation of Estonia's creative legacy. As the years unfolded, the art collection found its way back to Kadriorg Palace, where it could be fully showcased and celebrated. This transition paved the way for the restored palace and the grandeur of the Kumu Art Museum. Today, the Estonian Knighthood House serves as a bastion of artistic education and exploration as it houses the prestigious Estonian Academy of Arts. The building's walls reverberate with the passion and ingenuity of aspiring artists, designers, and creatives who hone their craft within its hallowed spaces. However, change is imminent, as the Estonian Academy of Arts prepares to embark on a new chapter in 2016. A reconstructed historical factory building in the vibrant Kalamaja quarter will soon become its home, ensuring the continuous growth and evolution of Estonia's artistic landscape.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tallinn/Estonian%20Knighthood%20House.jpg"
 },
