  "Monument": "Narikala Fortress",
  "Short": "Welcome to Narikala Fortress, an ancient stronghold perched on a steep hill, overlooking the beautiful city of Tbilisi and the Mtkvari River. Established as early as the 4th century AD under King Varaz-Bakur, it has stood the test of time, withstanding Persian invasions and Mongol rule. The fortress comprises two walled sections between Tbilisi's sulfur baths and botanical gardens. At its heart, you'll find the St Nicholas church, rebuilt in 1997, replicating the original 13th-century church that was lost in a fire. This church is decorated with frescos depicting scenes from the Bible and Georgia's history, making it a vibrant canvas of religious and cultural narrative. Despite the damages caused by the 1827 earthquake, Narikala remains a symbol of Tbilisi's historical resilience.",
  "Medium": "Step into history at Narikala Fortress, an ancient citadel overlooking the stunning views of Tbilisi and the Mtkvari River. This fortress, built as early as the 4th century AD during the reign of King Varaz-Bakur, has weathered the storm of various invasions and occupations over the centuries, from the Persians to the Mongols, who renamed it Narin Qala meaning Little Fortress.  The fortification, positioned between Tbilisi's sulfur baths and botanical gardens, is a testament to the architectural prowess of the times. It consists of two walled sections, each revealing different layers of Tbilisi's historical narrative. Notably, the majority of the extant fortifications are from the 16th and 17th centuries, highlighting the city's continuous ability to rebuild and evolve.  The centerpiece of the fortress is the St Nicholas church, which was reconstructed in 1997 after a devastating fire destroyed the original 13th-century church. The new structure stays true to the prescribed cross type of architecture, with doors on three sides. The interior is adorned with frescos, presenting scenes from the Bible and the annals of Georgian history, thus providing an artistic glimpse into the religious and cultural evolution of Georgia.  Unfortunately, an earthquake in 1827 caused significant damage to parts of the fortress, leading to their demolition. Despite these events, Narikala Fortress stands today as a symbol of Georgia's enduring spirit, offering visitors a unique insight into the country's rich history.",
  "Long": "Embark on a historical journey at Narikala Fortress, an ancient stronghold that dominates the skyline of Tbilisi, Georgia's capital, and oversees the majestic Mtkvari River. According to legend, this ancient fortress was established in the 4th century AD during King Varaz-Bakur's reign. Over the centuries, it has endured various invasions, shifts in rule, and the relentless march of time, but its walls tell a story of resilience and persistence.  Nestled between Tbilisi's therapeutic sulfur baths and lush botanical gardens, Narikala Fortress is a historic treasure trove waiting to be discovered. It's composed of two walled sections, each with their own distinct narratives. Although it initially fell into Persian hands, it was reclaimed by the kings of Kartli in the 5th century. It experienced significant expansion in the 7th century under the Umayyads and later under King David the Builder in the 11th century.  Interestingly, the fortress received its present name from the Mongols who, impressed by its formidable nature, named it Narin Qala, translating to Little Fortress. Despite its title, there's nothing 'little' about the history and culture enshrined within its walls. The existing fortifications mainly date back to the 16th and 17th centuries, silently narrating tales of past inhabitants and their determination to safeguard their city.  At the heart of Narikala is the recently restored St Nicholas church. Although the original 13th-century church succumbed to a fire, the reconstructed version, completed in 1996-1997, successfully mirrors its predecessor. It adheres to the prescribed cross architectural style, with doors gracing three sides of the structure.  The inner sanctum of St Nicholas church offers a vibrant canvas of Georgia's religious and historical journey. Its walls are adorned with frescos, visually narrating scenes from the Bible as well as significant episodes from Georgia's history. These artistic renditions offer a unique opportunity to appreciate the intertwining of faith and history in this ancient land.  Tragically, an earthquake in 1827 significantly damaged parts of the fortress, resulting in some sections being demolished. However, like a phoenix, Narikala has risen from its ashes time and again, reinforcing its image as a symbol of Georgia's tenacity.  Today, as you wander around its ancient walls, gaze at the city sprawled below, and admire the artwork within the St Nicholas church, Narikala Fortress provides a mesmerizing snapshot of Georgia's past. It's more than just a historical monument; it's a testament to the resilience of a city that has successfully preserved its rich heritage while advancing into the future.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Narikala%20Fortress.jpg"
 },
