  "Monument": "Holy Trinity Cathedral of Tbilisi",
  "Short": "Welcome to the magnificent Holy Trinity Cathedral of Tbilisi, known as Sameba, a majestic symbol of Georgian spiritual and national revival. Constructed from 1995 to 2004, it's one of the largest religious buildings in the world by area and the third-tallest Eastern Orthodox cathedral. Celebrating 1,500 years of Georgian Orthodox Church's autocephaly and 2,000 years from Jesus's birth, Sameba marries traditional Georgian architectural styles with Byzantine undertones. Within, you'll find stunning murals painted by a team led by Amiran Goglidze, adorning the nine chapels, five of which are underground. Constructed mostly by anonymous donations, this sacred space represents Georgia's unity and resilience.",
  "Medium": "Step into the grandeur of the Holy Trinity Cathedral of Tbilisi, commonly referred to as Sameba. It's not only the main cathedral of the Georgian Orthodox Church, but also an emblem of Georgian national and spiritual renewal. Constructed between 1995 and 2004, it stands as one of the world's largest religious buildings by area and the third-tallest Eastern Orthodox cathedral.  The cathedral was erected to commemorate 1,500 years of autocephaly of the Georgian Orthodox Church and 2,000 years since Jesus's birth. The architecture reflects a fusion of traditional Georgian styles punctuated by Byzantine influences. Designed by Archil Mindiashvili, Sameba graces the Elia Hill, overlooking the historic Avlabari neighborhood and the Kura River.  Its impressive interior hosts nine chapels, including five located underground. A team led by Amiran Goglidze meticulously painted the murals inside, providing a visually rich narrative of faith. Sameba‚Äôs floor, constructed of marble tiles, and its altar, soon to be adorned with mosaic, amplify its spiritual aura.  Sameba was consecrated in 2004 on St. George's Day in a ceremony attended by high-ranking representatives of Orthodox Churches worldwide and national leaders. Its construction, sponsored by anonymous donations from businessmen and citizens, is a testament to Georgian unity and resilience.",
  "Long": "Welcome to the imposing Holy Trinity Cathedral of Tbilisi, affectionately known as Sameba. Towering over Georgia's capital, this cathedral serves as the heart of the Georgian Orthodox Church. Built between 1995 and 2004, Sameba ranks as the third-tallest Eastern Orthodox cathedral globally and one of the largest religious buildings by total area.  The idea to build Sameba, conceived in 1989, aimed to commemorate 1,500 years of autocephaly of the Georgian Orthodox Church and 2,000 years since Jesus's birth. However, civil unrest delayed this ambitious plan until 1995 when construction finally commenced.  Sameba's architectural design, crafted by Archil Mindiashvili, is an elegant blend of traditional Georgian styles with Byzantine undertones, paying tribute to Georgia's historical architectural evolution. Rising from the historic neighborhood of Avlabari on Elia Hill, the cathedral overlooks the Kura River, offering a stunning view to those visiting this sacred site.  Stepping inside, you'll find an extraordinary interior featuring nine chapels, five of which are nestled underground. Each chapel tells its own story through the beautiful murals painted by Amiran Goglidze and his team. With a floor of marble tiles and an altar soon to be embellished with mosaic, the cathedral is a breathtaking manifestation of Georgian craftsmanship.  The cathedral's completion in 2004 was celebrated on St. George's Day, with its consecration attended by Orthodox Churches' high-ranking representatives, leaders of other religious communities in Georgia, and political figures. This event underlined the significance of Sameba as a beacon of national and spiritual revival. The fact that its construction was funded primarily by anonymous donations from various strata of society is a testament to the shared respect and dedication to the Georgian Orthodox Church.  The Sameba complex includes a free-standing bell-tower, the residence of the Patriarch, a monastery, clerical seminary, and theological academy, and several workshops, representing a comprehensive spiritual center for worship, learning, and reflection. Despite a somewhat controversial history regarding the land it occupies, which was once the Khojavank Armenian cemetery, Sameba stands as a testament to the resilience and unity of the Georgian people.  However, as visitors, while you marvel at its grandeur and appreciate the spiritual and artistic treasures housed within, it's essential to remember the checkered past of the land it occupies. This encourages a broader understanding of Georgia's intricate social fabric and history, underscoring the importance of mutual respect and peaceful coexistence between different cultures and faiths. In doing so, Sameba, in all its splendor, serves as a reminder of Georgia's enduring spirit and its path towards unity and prosperity.   ",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Holy%20Trinity%20Cathedral%20of%20Tbilisi.jpg"
 },
 {
  "Pais": "Georgia",
  "Ciudad": "Tbilisi",
  "District": "Tbilisi",
