  "Monument": "Freedom Square",
  "Short": "Welcome to Freedom Square, the pulsating heart of Tbilisi, Georgia! This square, situated at the eastern end of Rustaveli Avenue, is steeped in history, changing names with each shift in power, from Erivansky Square to Beria Square, Lenin Square, and finally, Freedom Square. Originally named after Ivan Paskevich, a general who conquered Erivan for the Russian Empire, the square saw its identity shift numerous times during the Soviet era. Today, it stands as a symbol of Georgia's sovereignty and resilience. You'll notice the Liberty Monument, a captivating statue of St George slaying the dragon, symbolizing the nation's victory over oppression. Nearby, a bust of Alexander Pushkin and the Tbilisi City Assembly embellish the area. The square has been the site of many important events, like the 1907 Tiflis bank robbery and the famous speech of U.S. President George W. Bush.",
  "Medium": "Welcome to the iconic Freedom Square, a central meeting point at the eastern end of Rustaveli Avenue in Tbilisi, Georgia. This square tells a story of changing times. Known as Erivansky Square during the Imperial Russia era, it was named after Ivan Paskevich, a Ukrainian general recognized for his conquest of Erivan for the Russian Empire. During the Soviet era, it transformed into Beria Square, then Lenin Square, reflecting the changing political dynamics.  In 1918, following the Russian Empire's fall, it was named Freedom Square, a symbol of Georgia's newly-found independence. Notably, this square has been the stage for significant historical events, like the 1907 Tiflis bank robbery, several mass demonstrations for Georgia's independence from the Soviet Union, and even an assassination attempt on U.S. President George W. Bush during his 2005 visit.  The captivating Liberty Monument is an unmissable feature, located at the square's heart. Created by Zurab Tsereteli, it portrays St George slaying the dragon, a symbolic representation of Georgia's victory over its oppressors. Nearby, you'll find a bust of renowned Russian poet Alexander Pushkin. The square also houses the Tbilisi City Assembly and the former Bank of Georgia head office, which are architectural gems.  The square's vibrant energy and historical significance make it a must-visit spot for any traveler, and its central location makes it a perfect starting point for exploring the beautiful city of Tbilisi.",
  "Long": "Greetings from the heart of Tbilisi, Georgia! You are standing in Freedom Square, a place that is more than just a geographical location, but a tapestry of Georgia's history, struggle, and ultimate triumph over oppression. Located at the eastern end of Rustaveli Avenue, this square carries with it a fascinating history.  Under Imperial Russia, this square was known as Erivansky Square, named after Ivan Paskevich, a Ukrainian general who earned his title by conquering Erivan (now Yerevan) for the Russian Empire. But as political tides shifted, so did the square's name. During the Soviet era, it became Beria Square, then Lenin Square, mirroring the change in power and ideologies of the time.  It was only after 1918, when the First Georgian Republic was founded following the Russian Empire's collapse, that the square got its current name: Freedom Square. This was more than a name; it was a declaration of Georgia's hard-fought sovereignty. Since then, the square has been a stage for momentous historical events. It was the site of the 1907 Tiflis bank robbery and various mass demonstrations calling for Georgia's independence from the Soviet Union. Even in recent history, Freedom Square was where U.S. President George W. Bush and Georgian President Mikheil Saakashvili addressed a crowd of around 100,000 people in 2005, marking the end of World War II's 60th anniversary.  Freedom Square isn't just a place of political significance. It's a hub of culture and art, too. The most prominent feature is the Liberty Monument, a stunning piece by Zurab Tsereteli, featuring St George triumphantly slaying the dragon. This isn't just a heroic scene from legend; it's a metaphor for Georgia's victory over its past oppressors. Nearby, a bust of Alexander Pushkin, a famed Russian poet, adds to the square's artistic allure.  On the square's northern side, you'll notice an open space with a fountain, a quiet place to rest and take in the area's vibrancy. This place was once the burial ground of Simon Ter-Petrossian, famously known as Kamo, a renowned communist figure whose remains were moved to an undisclosed location during Stalin's rule.  Surrounding the square, several important buildings add to its grandeur. The Tbilisi City Assembly, the former Bank of Georgia head office, and the Courtyard by Marriott Tbilisi all contribute to the unique architectural landscape. There are also ongoing works to accommodate the Old Tbilisi local government office here.  The significance of Freedom Square goes beyond its historical and artistic importance. It stands as a symbol of the spirit of the Georgian people - a testament to their enduring resilience and their journey from subjugation to freedom. Every monument, every street branching out from it, holds a piece of the country's vibrant history, making Freedom Square an indispensable part of your journey through Tbilisi, Georgia.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Freedom%20Square.jpg"
 },
