  "Monument": "Rustaveli Avenue",
  "Short": "Welcome to Rustaveli Avenue, Tbilisi's vibrant heart named after the renowned medieval Georgian poet, Shota Rustaveli! This central avenue, formerly known as Golovin Street, is a 1.5 km stretch starting at Freedom Square, filled with rich architecture, art, and history. Along this street, you'll discover key landmarks including the Parliament of Georgia, Georgian National Opera Theater, and the Georgian Museum of Fine Arts. A highlight is the Rustaveli State Academic Theater, a symbol of Georgia's flourishing cultural scene. Be sure to explore the countless cafes, shops, and restaurants that pepper this avenue. Remember the 1989 April 9 tragedy, when a peaceful protest on this very avenue was met with Soviet force. Today, Rustaveli remains a site of public expression, while also hosting outdoor exhibitions and performances, reflecting the vibrant spirit of Tbilisi. ",
  "Medium": "Welcome to Rustaveli Avenue, Tbilisi's vibrant heart named after the renowned medieval Georgian poet, Shota Rustaveli! This central avenue, formerly known as Golovin Street, is a 1.5 km stretch starting at Freedom Square, filled with rich architecture, art, and history. Along this street, you'll discover key landmarks including the Parliament of Georgia, Georgian National Opera Theater, and the Georgian Museum of Fine Arts. A highlight is the Rustaveli State Academic Theater, a symbol of Georgia's flourishing cultural scene. Be sure to explore the countless cafes, shops, and restaurants that pepper this avenue. Remember the 1989 April 9 tragedy, when a peaceful protest on this very avenue was met with Soviet force. Today, Rustaveli remains a site of public expression, while also hosting outdoor exhibitions and performances, reflecting the vibrant spirit of Tbilisi.  Medium Text (300 words):  Welcome to the pulsating heart of Tbilisi, Rustaveli Avenue. Named after Shota Rustaveli, a medieval Georgian poet, this central avenue unfolds a rich tapestry of history, art, and culture. It stretches approximately 1.5 km from Freedom Square, functioning as Tbilisi's main artery with numerous governmental, public, cultural, and business buildings.  Your journey starts at the Rustaveli Cinema, the biggest in Georgia. Opposite it, you'll see the Youth Palace and the former Parliament Building of Georgia. The Kashveti Church, nestled between the Art House of Tbilisi and the Art Museum, offers a spiritual retreat amid the bustling city. The stunning Georgian National Opera Theater and the Rustaveli State Academic Theater, symbols of Georgia's rich cultural heritage, lie ahead.  Rustaveli Avenue is a medley of modern and 20th-century architecture, with numerous cafes, shops, and entertainment places adding to its allure. History lovers will find the avenue intriguing for the April 9 tragedy, a poignant event in 1989 where Soviet forces killed many peaceful protesters.  Despite its historical weight, Rustaveli Avenue is a vibrant urban space today, playing host to public protests, outdoor exhibitions, performances, and more. Accessible via the Tbilisi Metro, it's one metro stop away from another historical artery of Tbilisi, Agmashenebeli Avenue. Come, take a stroll and let Rustaveli Avenue's rich history, architecture, and vibrant cultural life enthral you!",
  "Long": "Welcome to Rustaveli Avenue, a captivating blend of history, culture, and urban vibrancy, nestled in the heart of Tbilisi, Georgia. Named after Shota Rustaveli, the celebrated medieval Georgian poet, this central avenue is the lifeblood of Tbilisi. Formerly known as Golovin Street, Rustaveli Avenue starts at Freedom Square, extending about 1.5 km before transitioning into Kostava Street.  As you embark on your exploration, the first landmark to greet you is Rustaveli Cinema, Georgia's largest. Across the cinema, you'll spot the Youth Palace and the former Parliament Building of Georgia, all testament to Tbilisi's rich architectural heritage. The Kashveti Church, sandwiched between the Art House of Tbilisi and the Art Museum, provides a tranquil sanctuary amid the bustling avenue.  Moving forward, you'll encounter the Georgian National Opera Theater, a grand edifice showcasing Georgia's theatrical prowess. Next, the Rustaveli State Academic Theater further encapsulates the nation's thriving cultural scene. The avenue is also home to the Georgian Academy of Sciences, the Georgian Museum of Fine Arts, and the Simon Janashia Museum of Georgia, each offering fascinating insights into Georgia's intellectual and artistic pursuits. Completing the architectural showcase are the Biltmore Hotel Tbilisi and numerous other buildings adding to the avenue's visual appeal.  However, Rustaveli Avenue is not just about grand edifices. It's about the everyday vibrancy of cafes, shops, and restaurants that line its sides, inviting you to taste the local flavors, shop for unique souvenirs, or simply sit back and watch the world go by. With a blend of modern and 20th-century architecture, the avenue is a visual feast for architecture enthusiasts.  Rustaveli Avenue also holds a significant place in Georgia's political history. In 1989, the avenue witnessed a somber moment in Georgian history, known as the April 9 tragedy. Tens of thousands of Georgians had gathered before the House of Government on Rustaveli Avenue for a peaceful demonstration that was brutally quelled by Soviet forces, resulting in numerous fatalities.  Today, while the avenue continues to be a venue for public protests, it has also transformed into a lively cultural hub. It hosts a variety of outdoor exhibitions, performances, and events, demonstrating the city's dynamic cultural scene. Accessible via the Tbilisi Metro and various bus lines, Rustaveli Avenue is conveniently connected to other parts of the city. It's one metro stop away from Agmashenebeli Avenue, another historical artery of Tbilisi.  Rustaveli Avenue, with its rich history, impressive architecture, and vibrant street life, is a microcosm of Tbilisi itself. It represents the city's past struggles, present dynamism, and hopeful future. So, whether you're a history buff, an architecture enthusiast, a cultural connoisseur, or a food lover, Rustaveli Avenue promises a delightful exploration and an unforgettable experience. Welcome to the pulsating heart of Tbilisi!   ",
