  "Monument": "Peace Bridge",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Bridge of Peace, a striking modern landmark in Tbilisi's historic heart! Unveiled in 2010, this pedestrian bridge gracefully spans the Kura River, linking the Rike Park with the Old town. With its wave-like steel and glass design lit by thousands of LEDs, the bridge offers stunning views of Tbilisi's iconic landmarks, such as the Metekhi Church and the Narikala Fortress. The mesmerizing interactive light display activates 90 minutes before sunset until 90 minutes after sunrise, with patterns that travel in waves, converge, and twinkle like stars. Walking along, you'll notice motion sensors trigger the embedded LEDs in the railings, creating a personalised light show for every passerby. Despite some controversy over its futuristic design within the historical district, the Bridge of Peace has become a beloved symbol of Tbilisi, connecting its past with the present.",
  "Medium": "Welcome to the Bridge of Peace, an iconic fusion of history and modernity nestled in the heart of Tbilisi. Spanning 150 metres across the Kura River, this bow-shaped pedestrian bridge connects Rike Park with Old Tbilisi. It was unveiled in 2010, becoming an integral pedestrian crossing and a beloved symbol of the capital.  The bridge was designed by Italian architect Michele De Lucchi, who also designed Tbilisi's Ceremonial Palace of Georgia and the Ministry of Internal Affairs. As you stroll, the bridge's curvature and marine-animal-like structure encased in steel and glass offer stunning panoramas of Tbilisi's landmarks, including the Metekhi Church, the statue of city founder Vakhtang Gorgasali, and the Narikala Fortress.  The Bridge of Peace truly comes alive at night with a spectacular light show. Its canopy, fitted with 1,208 custom LED fixtures, displays four different lighting patterns every hour, creating a mesmerizing visual performance that lights up in waves, converges from both ends, illuminates the entire canopy, and twinkles like stars.  Walk along the bridge and feel the magic as the motion sensors trigger the embedded LEDs in the glass railings, providing an illusion of the bridge lighting up just for you. Moreover, an hourly Morse code message rendering the periodic table of elements crosses the two parapets, symbolizing life and peace between people.  Although initially met with criticism due to its modern design overshadowing the historic district, the Bridge of Peace has won hearts over time. Its unique blend of art, design, and technology, encapsulated in the playful nickname 'Always Ultra Bridge', only enhances its charm. Join us in celebrating Tbilisi's past, present, and future on this remarkable bridge.",
  "Long": "Welcome to the Bridge of Peace, a marvel of modern architecture blending seamlessly into Tbilisi's historic cityscape. Unveiled in 2010, this bow-shaped pedestrian bridge stretches 150 metres over the Kura River, connecting the green expanse of Rike Park with the cobblestone streets of Old Tbilisi.  The brainchild of Italian architect Michele De Lucchi, who also designed Tbilisi's Ceremonial Palace of Georgia and the Ministry of Internal Affairs, the bridge's distinctive wave-like design has often been compared to a marine creature. Its steel and glass canopy, lit by over a thousand custom LEDs, has turned the bridge into a nocturnal spectacle.  As you meander along the bridge, you'll be greeted by panoramic views of Tbilisi's landmarks. On one side, admire the grandeur of the Metekhi Church, the statue of the city's founder, Vakhtang Gorgasali, and the formidable Narikala Fortress. On the other side, catch sight of the Baratashvili Bridge and the Ceremonial Palace of Georgia.  The Bridge of Peace is more than just a crossing‚Äîit's an immersive light show. From 90 minutes before sunset until 90 minutes after sunrise, the bridge transforms into a mesmerizing display of light. The canopy lights up with four different patterns every hour: waves that roll across the length, converging bands of light that meet in the middle, an all-encompassing glow followed by total darkness, and a starry twinkle.  This magical experience doesn't end there. Embedded in the glass railings are linear LED arrays that light up as you walk, thanks to 240 motion sensors. This interactive feature gives the illusion that the bridge is lighting up just for you, making each crossing a personalized event. Additionally, an hourly Morse code message that spells out the periodic table of elements traverses the two parapets. This communication has been interpreted by the lighting designer Philippe Martinaud as a celebration of life and peace between people.  Despite its artistic brilliance, the Bridge of Peace initially stirred controversy. Critics argued that its contemporary design dominated and obscured the historical Old Tbilisi. Over time, however, the bridge has become an integral part of the cityscape and a beloved symbol of the capital. Its unusual shape even earned it the playful nickname 'Always Ultra Bridge', after its supposed resemblance to a ladies' maxi-pad.  The Bridge of Peace stands as a testament to Tbilisi's journey from a historic town to a burgeoning metropolis. Its mix of modern design and interactive technology, nestled among centuries-old landmarks, embodies the city's progressive spirit. As you walk across this bridge, you're not just crossing the Kura River‚Äîyou're traversing through Tbilisi's rich past, vibrant present, and promising future. So come, experience this spellbinding fusion of history, innovation, and art. Welcome to the Bridge of Peace.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Peace%20Bridge.jpg"
 },
