  "Monument": "Rike Park",
  "Short": "Welcome to Rike Park, a vibrant oasis in the heart of Tbilisi! This modern recreational area, shaped like a large-scale map of Georgia, lies on the left bank of the Kura River. Accessed via the remarkable Bridge of Peace, or the steps from Avlabari, it's a hub of activity. Here, you'll find a dynamic mix of architectural wonders and family-friendly attractions, from a giant chess board to a grand white piano. The park is beautiful at night when thousands of LEDs illuminate the river and surrounding buildings. The music-playing fountain adds to the charm. Rike Park is also the starting point for the cable car ride up to the Narikala Fortress. Whether you're strolling through landscaped gardens, viewing art displays, or tasting traditional cuisines during Tbilisoba in October, Rike Park promises memorable moments! ",
  "Medium": "Welcome to Rike Park, a contemporary gem in Tbilisi's heart, offering a unique blend of nature, architecture, and cultural activities. Nestled on the Kura River's left bank, the park is laid out like a large-scale map of Georgia, its paths marking the country's various regions.  You can access the park via the stunning Bridge of Peace from the Old Town or descend the rocky steps from Avlabari. Once inside, be prepared to witness a fascinating mix of recreational attractions, including a giant chess board and a magnificent white grand piano. There are interactive features for children, like a playful maze, a climbing wall, and various playground equipment, providing ample fun for the whole family.  Rike Park transforms into a magical realm at night, with thousands of LED lights illuminating the river, the Bridge of Peace, and the park's surroundings. The choreographed water-and-light show of the park's fountain makes it an enchanting place to spend an evening.  For the adventurous, the park houses the starting point for the thrilling cable car ride that whisks you across the Old Town and up to Narikala Fortress. You'll experience breathtaking panoramic views of the cityscape from the glass-bottomed cable car.  Despite being one of Tbilisi's youngest parks, Rike Park has quickly become a must-visit destination for tourists and locals alike. The park hosts a captivating display of art in the summer and the festive Tbilisoba event in October, where visitors can savor traditional cuisines from across Georgia. With a future concert hall and exhibition center in the pipeline, Rike Park continues to expand its offering, promising more enchanting experiences to its visitors.",
  "Long": "Greetings from Rike Park, an alluring fusion of natural beauty, innovative architecture, and vibrant culture in Tbilisi's heart. Occupying a scenic spot on the Kura River's left bank, this artistically designed park presents a large-scale map of Georgia from a bird's eye view. The winding pathways portray the country's diverse regions, offering an intriguing geographical exploration.  Access to Rike Park is an adventure in itself. You can either cross the iconic Bridge of Peace, an architectural masterpiece connecting the Old Town, or descend from Avlabari's rocky steps. Despite initial controversy about the bridge's modern design clashing with the historic cityscape, it has become an integral part of Tbilisi's identity, providing a spectacular entrance to the park.  Once inside, you're welcomed by a plethora of attractions that cater to visitors of all ages. Play a game on the giant chess board, tinkle the ivories on the grand white piano, or watch children delight in the playground equipment, artificial climbing wall, and fun-filled maze. The beautifully landscaped gardens and quiet corners offer tranquil spaces to relax amidst the city's hustle and bustle.  Rike Park truly comes alive at night. Thousands of LED lights illuminate the park, the river, and the surrounding architecture, creating a stunning nocturnal spectacle. The captivating light and water show of the park's fountain adds to the enchanting atmosphere, making it a perfect spot for evening walks or romantic rendezvous.  For thrill-seekers, the park serves as the launch point for a cable car journey across the Old Town and up to the Narikala Fortress. With even the cable car's floor glassed, you'll enjoy panoramic views of Tbilisi that leave a lasting impression.  Despite being one of Tbilisi's youngest recreational areas, Rike Park has rapidly gained popularity. In addition to its diverse attractions, it hosts lively events throughout the year. During summer, the park becomes an open-air art gallery, where you can admire stunning artwork and even purchase a piece to take home.  One of the park's highlights is Tbilisoba, a beautiful annual event held in October that celebrates Tbilisi's city day. During Tbilisoba, the park is filled with festive stalls offering traditional cuisines from every region of Georgia. This vibrant festival offers a unique opportunity to taste Georgia's culinary diversity while immersing yourself in local culture.  Future plans for Rike Park include a concert hall and exhibition center, housed in two large metallic tubes at the park's northern end. Although these structures are currently unfinished, they represent the city's commitment to enhancing Rike Park's offerings.  As you stroll through the park, you'll encounter vendors selling ice cream, toys, and sweet treats, or come across illustrators who can paint a personal portrait as a memento of your visit. Each visit to Rike Park brings new experiences and surprises, ensuring it remains a cherished destination for tourists and residents alike. It is more than just a park ‚Äì it's a symbol of Tbilisi's spirit, blending tradition, innovation, and community in one remarkable space.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Rike%20Park.jpg"
 },
