  "Monument": "Mtatsminda Park",
  "Short": "Welcome to Mtatsminda Park, a picturesque park perched atop Mount Mtatsminda in Tbilisi. Founded by the Soviet government in the 1930s, the park was once among the most visited in the USSR. Today, it offers a variety of thrilling rides such as carousels, water slides, a roller-coaster, and a fascinating dark ride, the Ghost Castle. Don't miss the 65-meter-high Ferris Wheel, from where you can enjoy a splendid view over Tbilisi. The park is accessible via a funicular, an attraction in itself. Despite its complex history involving property seizures and a transformation into a modern theme park by Georgian billionaire Badri Patarkatsishvili, the park is now a beloved recreational spot in Tbilisi.",
  "Medium": "Step into the enchanting Mtatsminda Park, a beautifully landscaped gem located at the peak of Mount Mtatsminda in Tbilisi. Overlooking the Georgian capital, this park, founded in the 1930s by the Soviet government, was once noted as the third most visited public park in the USSR. Nowadays, it sprawls over 100 hectares at a height of 770 meters, making it the highest point in Tbilisi.  The park is home to a multitude of attractions, from carousels and water slides to a roller-coaster and a spectacular dark ride, Ghost Castle. The centerpiece is the Giant Wheel, a 65-meter-high Ferris wheel that completes one revolution in 10‚Äì12 minutes, offering breathtaking panoramic views of the city.  Getting to the park is an adventure itself with the Tbilisi Funicular, a ropeway railway built in 1905, offering an exciting ride from Chonkadze street to the park.  The park has had an intriguing history. It was transformed into a 21st-century theme park by the late Georgian billionaire Badri Patarkatsishvili. However, his opposition to the National Movement Party led to a controversial seizure of his assets, including Mtatsminda Park, in 2007. Following his death and a protracted legal battle, the park was returned to Patarkatsishvili's family in 2011.",
  "Long": "Welcome to Mtatsminda Park, a veritable haven nestled at the zenith of Mount Mtatsminda, towering over Tbilisi, the capital of Georgia. The park, spanning over 100 hectares and perched at a height of 770 meters, offers not only a peaceful respite from city life but also a thrilling array of amusement rides and attractions.  Established by the Soviet government in the 1930s, Mtatsminda Park was once the third most frequented public park in the entire USSR. Today, it retains its allure with a combination of history and fun. You'll find everything here from carousels, water slides, a roller-coaster, to the mysteriously intriguing Ghost Castle, a dark ride filled with horror scenes and special effects.  One of the park's standout attractions is the Giant Wheel, a Ferris wheel standing at an impressive 65 meters high. As it makes a leisurely revolution every 10‚Äì12 minutes, riders are treated to an unparalleled, breathtaking view of Tbilisi's skyline.  The journey to the park is an experience unto itself. The Tbilisi Funicular, a historic ropeway railway established in 1905, connects Chonkadze street with the park. The funicular journey, with its changing gradients and panoramic views, is an attraction in its own right, linking the heart of the city with the peace and tranquility of Mtatsminda Park.  However, Mtatsminda Park is more than just a collection of attractions. It's a place steeped in history. In the early 2000s, the late Georgian billionaire Badri Patarkatsishvili and his wife, Inna Gudavadze, began a transformation of the park, shaping it into a 21st-century theme park. Patarkatsishvili owned the park as part of a charitable project, along with other commercial assets in Georgia.  In 2007, due to Patarkatsishvili's political opposition to the National Movement Party, he fell out of favor with then-President Mikhail Saakashvili. His assets, including Mtatsminda Park, were controversially seized by the government. After Patarkatsishvili's death in 2008, his widow, Inna Gudavadze, fought for the return of the park and other assets, believing it her duty to continue her husband's projects for Georgia and its people. After a four-year-long legal struggle, the park was finally returned to the Patarkatsishvili family in 2011.  Today, Mtatsminda Park stands as a testament to the enduring spirit of the Georgian people. It's a symbol of the nation's past and its journey into the future. For visitors, it's not just a fun-filled excursion but a glimpse into Georgia's rich cultural and historical tapestry. It's more than just a park‚Äîit's a piece of living history.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Mtatsminda%20Park.jpg"
 },
