  "Monument": "Chardin Street",
  "Short": "Welcome to Chardin Street! Nestled in the bustling district of Upper Kala, this vibrant area is a true embodiment of Tbilisi's captivating spirit. Originated in the 19th century, the street was formerly known as Dark Row due to its dense cluster of shops and workshops. Today, Chardin Street is a popular haunt filled with art galleries, souvenir shops, and a hint of modern architecture. It owes its name to Jan Chardin, a French explorer who visited in 1863. As you stroll along, you'll encounter a small square and park adorned with the bronze Tamada statue, a symbol of Georgian hospitality, discovered in ancient Vani. Lastly, don't forget to visit the nearby historic Sioni Cathedral and old caravanserais. ",
  "Medium": "Welcome, adventurers! Today, we explore the delightful Chardin Street, nestled within the heart of Tbilisi's Upper Kala district. Founded in the late 19th century, Chardin Street, or the erstwhile Dark Row, was once a busy marketplace brimming with shops and workshops. This historic street owes its name to the French explorer Jan Chardin, who marveled at Tbilisi's beauty in 1863.  Chardin Street is now a bustling attraction teeming with local art galleries and souvenir shops that perfectly encapsulate Georgian tradition and culture. Wander around, and you'll spot the touch of modernity with new-age buildings striking a balance with the old-world charm of the place. These recent architectural additions provide a visual distinction between Chardin and the neighboring Bamba Street.  The starting point of Chardin Street features a charming square and park. Here stands a bronze statue fondly known as Tamada or toast-maker. This is a replica of an ancient statue unearthed in Vani, which dates back to the 7th century BC. A toast-maker is a traditional figure in Georgian feasts, epitomizing the warmth and hospitality of this country.  The street's charm lies not just in its lively atmosphere but also its proximity to other historic sites. The renowned Sioni Cathedral and old caravanserais are within a stone's throw, making Chardin Street an ideal starting point for your Tbilisi adventure.",
  "Long": "Greetings, dear travelers! Allow me to introduce you to one of Tbilisi's most beloved destinations, Chardin Street. Situated within the bustling Upper Kala district and sandwiched between Vakhtang Gorgasali and Sioni streets, Chardin Street is an enchanting blend of history and modernity.  Originating in the 19th century, the street was formerly known as Dark Row - a dense and vibrant hub filled with shops and workshops. This bustling marketplace was later named Chardin Street, honoring the French explorer Jan Chardin who visited Tbilisi in 1863. Over time, the street has experienced a series of changes, transforming from a busy market street to a major cultural destination.  Chardin Street today is a hotspot for those looking to immerse themselves in Georgian culture and history. Its winding pathways are lined with local art galleries displaying a variety of artistic styles, ranging from traditional Georgian art to more contemporary works. If you're on the hunt for unique souvenirs, the myriad of eclectic shops won't disappoint. You'll find a treasure trove of traditional Georgian crafts, handwoven rugs, and intricate jewelry that serve as perfect mementos of your Tbilisi journey.  In recent times, the face of Chardin Street has seen an influx of modern style buildings that tastefully blend with the historic architecture. This blend of the old and new symbolizes Tbilisi's evolving urban landscape, marking a clear boundary between Chardin Street and its neighboring Bamba Street.  One of the notable highlights of Chardin Street is the bronze statue known as Tamada situated in the street's initial square and park. This figure, a toast-maker, is a key figure in traditional Georgian feasts, symbolizing the nation's unique customs and warm hospitality. The statue is a replica of an ancient artifact discovered during excavations in Vani dating back to the 7th century BC.  As you walk further down the street, you'll discover more of Tbilisi's architectural splendors. The proximity of Chardin Street to the historic Sioni Cathedral and old caravanserais add to its allure. The Sioni Cathedral, named after Mount Zion in Jerusalem, stands as a symbol of Tbilisi's religious heritage, and the nearby caravanserais remind us of the city's vibrant past as a stop along the Silk Road.  But Chardin Street isn't just a location to view relics of the past. It's a thriving, bustling part of the city, brimming with cafes, restaurants, and bars that offer local and international cuisine. After exploring, you can unwind at one of these local establishments, savoring the famous Georgian wine or trying traditional dishes such as Khinkali and Khachapuri.  In essence, Chardin Street is more than just a street. It is a vibrant hub of cultural life in Tbilisi, offering a vivid snapshot of the city's past and present. It's a place where history comes to life, and where the hustle and bustle of city life combines with the timeless charm of Georgian tradition. So, take your time, explore, and soak up the unique spirit of Tbilisi right here on Chardin Street.",
