  "Monument": "Anchiskhati Basilica",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Anchiskhati Basilica of St Mary, Tbilisi's oldest surviving church dating back to the 6th century. Established by King Dachi of Iberia, the basilica became home to the treasured 12th-century icon of the Savior in 1675, now residing at the Art Museum of Georgia. Over centuries, the basilica underwent several transformations, most notably in the 1870s when a dome was added. A symbol of resilience, the basilica, despite periods of turmoil and secular use, was restored to its 17th-century appearance in 1964, and religious use resumed in 1991. Marvel at the basilica's unique architecture - a three-span design with entrances on three sides and admire the 19th-century paintings that adorn its interior. Don't miss out on the performances by the Anchiskhati Choir, renowned for their Georgian polyphonic choral music.",
  "Medium": "Dear travelers, welcome to the heart of Tbilisi - the Anchiskhati Basilica of St Mary. This basilica, built in the 6th century by King Dachi of Iberia, holds the title as the oldest surviving church in the city. Originally dedicated to the Virgin Mary, it was renamed Anchiskhati in 1675 when a revered icon of the Savior was moved here from the Ancha monastery to safeguard it from an Ottoman invasion.  The basilica's history is a testament to Georgia's turbulent past, having been rebuilt several times due to wars with Persians and Turks. A significant transformation occurred in the 1870s when a dome was added to the structure. During the Soviet era, the church served secular purposes - first as a museum of handicrafts, then an art studio. However, the 1500th Jubilee of Tbilisi saw a series of restorations from 1958 to 1964, reverting the church back to its 17th-century state. With Georgia's independence in 1991, the basilica returned to religious use.  As we step inside, observe the unique three-span basilica architecture, divided by horseshoe-shaped abutments - a testament to its ancient construction. Although originally built with yellow tuff stone, a 20th-century restoration introduced extensive use of brick. The altarpiece, commissioned by Catholicos Nikoloz Amilakhvari in 1683, stands out amongst the 19th-century paintings.  The basilica isn't just a historic monument, but also a vibrant cultural center. The world-renowned Anchiskhati Choir, known for their Georgian polyphonic choral music, calls this place home. Ensure to catch one of their enchanting performances.",
  "Long": "Greetings, fellow explorers! Let's step back in time to the 6th century with the oldest surviving church in Tbilisi - the Anchiskhati Basilica of St Mary. King Dachi of Iberia, who made Tbilisi his capital, laid the foundations of this historic structure, originally dedicated to the Virgin Mary. The name 'Anchiskhati' was adopted in 1675 when the precious icon of the Savior, a masterpiece by the 12th-century goldsmith Beka Opizari, was relocated here from the Ancha monastery in present-day Turkey to evade an Ottoman invasion.  The basilica's tumultuous history is a reflection of the wars between Georgia and its invaders, the Persians and Turks, which led to its repeated damage and restoration between the 15th and 17th centuries. Catholicos Domenti added a brick belfry near the Anchiskhati Basilica in 1675, and a dome was introduced in the 1870s, significantly altering its appearance.  During the Soviet period, religious activities at Anchiskhati Basilica were halted, and it transitioned into a museum for handicrafts and later an art studio. However, the 1500th Jubilee of Tbilisi in the late 1950s sparked a wave of restoration efforts, reviving the basilica's 17th-century facade. It wasn't until 1991, following Georgia's independence, that the church returned to its sacred purpose.  Walking through Anchiskhati Basilica is like traversing through time. The basilica showcases a unique three-span design divided by two horseshoe-shaped abutments, a mark of its antique construction. Originally built with blocks of yellow tuff stone, the church now prominently features bricks, a result of the restorations in the late 20th century. Despite having entrances on three sides, only the western one is currently in use.  Inside, the Anchiskhati Basilica boasts an array of artwork, the most remarkable of which is the altarpiece commissioned by Catholicos Nikoloz Amilakhvari in 1683. Alongside it, you will find paintings from the 19th century, each one a silent narrator of Georgia's rich history and religious traditions.  But Anchiskhati Basilica isn't just a silent witness to history. It's a thriving cultural center, home to the world-renowned Anchiskhati Choir, the leading exponent of Georgian polyphonic choral music. Listening to their harmonious melodies within the ancient walls of the basilica is a soul-stirring experience, a must-try during your visit.  From surviving invasions and wars to serving secular purposes and ultimately reclaiming its religious significance, Anchiskhati Basilica embodies the resilience of Georgian spirit. Its history, architecture, and cultural offerings make it an unmissable destination in Tbilisi. Whether you are an art lover, history buff, or a music enthusiast, the Anchiskhati Basilica of St Mary is sure to captivate your heart.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Anchiskhati%20Basilica.jpg"
 },
