  "Monument": "Dry Bridge Market",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Dry Bridge Market, the beating heart of Tbilisi! Since its inception during the post-communist 'dark 90s', this vibrant, open-air flea market has transformed into an intriguing tourist hotspot. You'll find it set on the Dry Bridge, no longer over water, but over a street. Browse the four sections: the flea market for a nostalgic walk through Soviet history, the art & crafts market for unique handmade items, the antiques market for a hidden treasure trove of retro items, and the book market, a peaceful riverside respite for book lovers. Come on weekends for the liveliest atmosphere, and remember to bring cash. From Soviet kitsch to authentic Georgian crafts, this market captures Georgia's rich and complex past in a fun and accessible way. Don't miss the nearby cafes for a gastronomic end to your market exploration!",
  "Medium": "Welcome to the unique experience of Tbilisi's Dry Bridge Market! It started as a survival means for locals after the collapse of communism in the 'dark 90s', and has since evolved into a bustling marketplace aimed at tourists. It's hosted on the Dry Bridge, which no longer spans the Mtkvari River, adding an ironic twist to its name. Today, it sports a more organized look, complete with stalls and purpose-built racks.  Our journey begins at the flea market, a living museum of Soviet-era artifacts. Navigate through tables and carpets laden with vintage items like old medals, Soviet memorabilia, and kilims. Next, we visit the art & handicrafts market tucked within the lush 9 March Park. Immerse yourself in local artistry with handmade items like feltwork, crochet socks, drinking horns, and musical instruments. Further exploration reveals the antiques market, a hidden trove of retro porcelain, ceramics, chandeliers, and more. The adventure concludes at the book market in Dedaena Park. It's the perfect spot for bookworms, offering old books, postcards, posters, and a picturesque river walk.  The Dry Bridge Market operates daily from 10 am to 5 pm, barring significant holidays or harsh weather. Weekends tend to be busier, providing a more vibrant experience. Cash is the sole form of payment here, and polite haggling is part of the culture. Be sure to enjoy the plethora of nearby eateries after your shopping spree, promising a delightful finish to your market exploration. ",
  "Long": "Welcome, dear explorers, to Tbilisi's Dry Bridge Market! As a testament to Georgia's resilience and entrepreneurial spirit, this market sprung up during the difficult 'dark 90s' following the collapse of communism. Today, it's a veritable tourist hotspot with a distinct structure, despite its humble beginnings.  The market is spread across the Dry Bridge, its name an echo of times when it spanned the Mtkvari River. Our exploration begins with the iconic flea market. Here, personal histories unfold through Soviet memorabilia, old medals, and vintage items. Expect to spot items that tell tales of the Soviet past, such as war medals, ID books, photographs, and many symbolic references to Lenin and Stalin. Mixed in with these, discover an eclectic array of Soviet-issue film cameras, caviar tins, and other items dating back to Georgia's days as a Socialist Republic. If you are a collector, you'll be captivated by the selection of coins, matchboxes, and stamps, though do inquire about their provenance.  As we stroll into the 9 March Park, we're welcomed by the vibrant art & handicrafts market. A medley of colorful felt shawls, knitted socks, Georgian drinking horns, decorative swords, and miniature clay qvevri dot the stands. An artist's paradise, the market houses an avenue where artists set up easels and display their work. A little further, the hidden antiques market awaits, where an exquisite collection of porcelain, ceramics, chandeliers, dinner sets, and vases beckons you to uncover hidden gems.  Our journey doesn't end here. The book market, located at the beautiful riverside Dedaena Park, offers a peaceful respite. Paris-style numbered booths present a collection of old books, postcards, posters, and other paper goods. The riverside walk here is an idyllic setting for a leisurely stroll.  The Dry Bridge Market is open from 10 am until 5 pm daily, with a short pause during major holidays and extreme weather. Though you can visit any day, weekends offer a more vibrant atmosphere, brimming with vendors and shoppers. Remember, cash is king here, as vendors only accept paper money. The art of polite haggling is also part of the experience, and it's an opportunity to engage with the vendors, who are usually quite friendly and intrigued by tourists.  Photography is generally accepted here, but do respect people's wishes if they prefer not to be photographed. Public restrooms are available for your convenience, including new facilities in the underpass inside Dedaena Park.  After you've filled your bags with unique treasures and memories, it's time to satiate your appetite. The surrounding area is peppered with delightful eateries and cafes. Atoneli Street is home to Caf√© Daphna, famous for its khinkali, while Santino is a haven for coffee lovers. A short walk along the river from the antique market takes you to one of the best restaurants in Tbilisi, The King and The Bird. If you're near Saarbrucken Square, Puri Guliani offers delectable breakfast, coffee, and cakes.  Whether you're a history buff, an art lover, a book enthusiast, or a curious traveler, the Dry Bridge Market is a tapestry of Georgia's past and present, its hardship and resilience, its tradition and creativity. A visit here is a walk through living history.   ",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Dry%20Bridge%20Market.jpg"
