  "Monument": "Botanical Garden",
  "Short": "Welcome to the National Botanical Garden of Georgia, Tbilisi's verdant gem. Dating back to at least 1625, it brims with over 3500 species of plants spread over 97 hectares. Once royal gardens, the area was renamed as Tbilisi Botanical Garden in 1845. It's not just about the flora, though. It's also home to historical landmarks, including the grave of the famed Azerbaijani writer Mirza Fatali Akhundov. Besides the botanical treasures, you will find a beautifully preserved 1909 tunnel, once Georgia's largest nightclub Gvirabi. Renowned scientists like Yuri Voronov have contributed to its development, enhancing its scientific and aesthetic importance. Today, the garden is a bustling scientific hub, housing six research departments and a nursery. If you‚Äôre visiting Tbilisi, don‚Äôt miss out on this harmonious blend of natural beauty and historical intrigue.",
  "Medium": "Welcome to the National Botanical Garden of Georgia, an oasis in the heart of Tbilisi. With a history dating back to 1625, this captivating green space has seen several transformations, from royal gardens to the renowned scientific hub it is today. With over 3500 species of plants dotting its 97 hectares of land, it's a biodiversity hotspot that's sure to fascinate botany enthusiasts and casual tourists alike.  What sets this garden apart is its rich historical tapestry. It's seen Persian invasions, played host to scholars like Yuri Voronov, and even survived the modernization of Tbilisi to become an essential city landmark. One of its most intriguing features is a tunnel built in 1909, once the site of Georgia's largest nightclub, Gvirabi. The central entrance, located at the foothills of Narikala Fortress, further adds to its allure.  Azerbaijani writer Mirza Fatali Akhundov rests here, giving the garden a literary connection. The garden has grown from strength to strength under the leadership of various Georgian scientists, becoming a centre for study and conservation. Today, it houses six research departments and a nursery, reflecting its commitment to preserving and propagating plant life.  The garden continues to receive international recognition and funding, helping to restore its historical monuments and support conservation work. As you meander through its pathways, admire its diverse plant life and soak in the history, you'll realize why the National Botanical Garden of Georgia is more than just a garden‚Äîit's a living testament to Georgia's enduring love for nature and history.",
  "Long": "Immerse yourself in the rich flora and history of the National Botanical Garden of Georgia. With its roots dating back to 1625, this green oasis nestled in the heart of Tbilisi has served as royal gardens, fortress gardens, and now stands as a beacon of botanical research and conservation.  The garden, spanning 97 hectares, is home to a stunning collection of over 3500 species, subspecies, and cultivars. This diversity extends from its picturesque landscaped areas to the wild natural vegetation. Each corner of the garden, be it the tropical plant orangery or the nursery, holds secrets of plant life waiting to be discovered.  The garden isn't just about its plants. Its rich tapestry of history is woven into every pathway and building. Once royal gardens, it fell victim to the Persian invasion of 1795 but resurrected itself in the early 19th century. The central entrance at the foothills of Narikala Fortress, the former Muslim cemetery, and the intriguing tunnel built in 1909, which used to house Georgia's largest nightclub Gvirabi, all tell tales of the garden's past.  Scholars like Yuri Voronov and notable Georgian scientists have contributed significantly to its development over the years. Their legacy endures in the six research departments within the garden: Caucasus Department of Rare Extinct and Medicinal Plants, Woody Plant Introduction, Public Relations and Marketing, Flowering and Landscape Design, Plant Conservation, and Plant and Soil Protection.  There's a literary touch to the garden too, with the grave of Azerbaijani writer Mirza Fatali Akhundov providing a poignant reminder of the garden's cultural significance. Its historical monuments, recently restored with international funding, add more layers to its rich historical narrative.  But the National Botanical Garden of Georgia isn't just living in the past. It's a vibrant hub of scientific research and education, with its laboratory of plant physiology, agrotechnics, nature protection, and scientific information departments of medicinal plants, and flowering-decorative plants. The Garden also gives back to the community by freely distributing fruit tree and vine seedlings, ornamental plants, and new vegetable varieties.  Over the centuries, the garden has served as a meeting place for the International Council of Botanical Gardens (BGCI) and has received funding from international organizations, cementing its place in the global botanical community. It was also the first garden in the South Caucasus to host a working meeting of the BGCI in 2009.  The garden continues to evolve while staying true to its roots. New additions include the Dendrological Museum of Woody Plants, a collectible plot of rare and extinct species of flora of Georgia, and Syringarium (Lilac Collection). Whether you are a botanist, a history enthusiast, or a traveler seeking tranquility amidst nature, the National Botanical Garden of Georgia offers an enchanting blend of botanical wonders and historical treasures.  In a visit to the National Botanical Garden of Georgia, you will not only encounter the breadth and depth of Georgia's botanical wealth, but you will also walk through chapters of Georgian history and scientific innovation. It's a must-visit destination that showcases the harmonious interplay between nature, history, and science in Georgia.",
