  "Monument": "Abanotubani",
  "Short": "Discover Abanotubani, Tbilisi's ancient district known for its unique sulphuric baths. Nestled at the foot of Narikala fort and on the Mtkvari River‚Äôs eastern bank, this neighborhood holds a cherished place in Georgian history. As per legend, King Vakhtang Gorgasali‚Äôs falcon discovered the hot springs here, leading to the foundation of Tbilisi. With architectural influences from the 17th and 18th century Iran, the baths are a sight to behold. They also offer more than just healing; they were once social hubs for feasts and relaxation. Don't miss this quintessential experience when in Tbilisi!",
  "Medium": "Step back in time as you explore Abanotubani, Tbilisi's ancient bath district, known for its distinct sulphuric baths. Strategically located at the foot of Narikala fort and alongside the Mtkvari River, it is not only a geographically significant location but also an iconic part of Georgian history. The legend goes that King Vakhtang Gorgasali‚Äôs falcon fell into the hot springs here, leading to the discovery that eventually founded Tbilisi.  These baths, known and recognized since ancient times, are not just therapeutic retreats but also valuable historical markers. They've attracted interest since the 13th century when there were 65 mineral water baths. Venetian traveler Marco Polo and Russian merchant Vasil Gagara were among the many who documented their experiences.  The architecture of these baths, predominantly built in the 17th and 18th centuries, reveals the strong influence of Iranian design. Visitors are awestruck by the beauty of these constructions located in Seydabad, marking the start of the ascent to the Botanical Garden.  But the baths were more than just places for healing or architectural admiration. They were once bustling social venues where citizens would spend their day swimming, relaxing, and even feasting. They were also a critical part of societal rituals, such as assessing the beauty of a prospective bride. When you visit Tbilisi, ensure to make time for a dip in these historical baths!",
  "Long": "Welcome to Abanotubani, Tbilisi's enchanting ancient district, renowned for its characteristic sulphuric baths. This district, situated at the base of the majestic Narikala fort and along the eastern bank of the Mtkvari River, is more than just a geographical landmark. It's a cornerstone of Georgian history and culture.  Abanotubani's significance is deeply intertwined with Tbilisi's founding story. According to legend, King Vakhtang Gorgasali's falcon fell into these hot springs. The king, entranced by the springs, decided to establish the city of Tbilisi around them.  The baths themselves have been recognized since ancient times for their restorative properties. As early as the 13th century, Tbilisi was home to 65 mineral water baths, a fact recorded by Arab geographer Ibn Hawqal, comparing them to the baths of Tiberias that boil without fire. Even famous Venetian traveler Marco Polo in the 13th-14th centuries, and Russian merchant Vasil Gagara in the 18th century, chronicled their experiences of these baths, testament to their international fame.  A stroll around Abanotubani will reveal the remarkable architectural influences from 17th and 18th century Iran. Most of the surviving baths were designed during this era, characterized by domed roofs and intricate brickwork. These baths, located in Seydabad, mark the start of the ascent to the Botanical Garden and thus, this area was named Abanotubani, translating to the bath district.  But Abanotubani's significance extends beyond just architecture and wellness. The baths were once integral to Tbilisi's social life. In the past, citizens spent entire days here, bathing, unwinding, and even partaking in lavish feasts. The baths were also entwined with societal customs - future mothers-in-law would traditionally inspect the beauty of a bride here.  Visiting these baths today is akin to experiencing a slice of Georgia's vibrant history and culture. As you immerse in the healing waters, soak in the historical atmosphere around you. Envision the bustling gatherings, elaborate feasts, and societal rituals that once took place within these walls.  Abanotubani is more than just a destination - it is a journey through Tbilisi's past, a tale of a city that rose from warm sulphuric waters. It is a testament to the country's cultural richness, architectural grandeur, and the indomitable spirit of its people. This is a place where the past and present seamlessly blend, offering a unique experience to every visitor. So, when you visit Tbilisi, do not miss a dip in these legendary baths. Abanotubani awaits you with its timeless charm and warmth.",
