  "Monument": "The Writer's House of Georgia",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Writer's House of Georgia, a captivating Art Nouveau mansion located in Sololaki, Tbilisi. Constructed by entrepreneur David Sarajishvili between 1903-1905, it's an architectural marvel combining neo-Baroque elements. A hub for Georgian literature, it's a place where famed literary group the Blue Horns convened in the early 1920s. The House experienced a significant renewal in 2008 and now hosts important literary events and even a restaurant in its garden during summer. Its 2017-launched residency program and the Museum of Repressed Writers, opened in 2021, provide rich insight into Georgia's literary history. A must-visit for literature lovers!",
  "Medium": "Step into the world of Georgian literature at the Writer's House of Georgia. This Art Nouveau mansion, nestled in the Sololaki district of Tbilisi, was built by entrepreneur David Sarajishvili between 1903-1905. It's a stunning display of architect Karl Zaar's work, blending neo-Baroque elements with an impressive terrace mosaic made from Villeroy and Boch tiles.  From the early 1920s, this House was a meeting place for the Blue Horns, a group of major figures in Georgian literature. The history of the House also has a darker side, with poet Paolo Iashvili tragically committing suicide here in 1937.  Revitalized in 2008, the Writer's House today serves as a center for numerous literary and cultural events. It also launched a residency program in 2017, attracting authors and enthusiasts from around the globe. With the support of Tbilisi - UNESCO World Book Capital 2021, the House inaugurated the Museum of Repressed Writers, designed by Mariam Natroshvili and Detu Jincharadze, featuring documents from the SovLab Research Laboratory.  The current director, Natasha Lomouri, has been leading the institution since 2011. While the House is a cherished symbol of Georgia's literary heritage, it also offers a delightful gastronomic experience, housing a restaurant in its garden during summer. Do not miss this unique combination of literature, history, and architecture! ",
  "Long": "The Writer's House of Georgia welcomes you with its grand architecture and rich literary history. Nestled in the charming Sololaki district of Tbilisi, this splendid Art Nouveau mansion is a tribute to the glory of Georgian literature. The House was built between 1903-1905 by entrepreneur David Sarajishvili under the skilled direction of architect Karl Zaar, masterfully blending neo-Baroque style elements. One of the unique features of the House is the terrace mosaic, meticulously crafted from tiles by Villeroy and Boch.  In the early 1920s, the House was a gathering spot for the Blue Horns group, a circle of avant-garde Georgian poets. It's also the place where the celebrated poet Paolo Iashvili tragically ended his life in 1937, adding a melancholic chapter to its history.  After 2008, the House underwent a renaissance, shifting its focus back to the promotion of literature. It has since become a significant venue for literary and cultural events, making it a pulsating center of Tbilisi's cultural life. The House launched a residency program in 2017, fostering a nurturing environment for writers and encouraging literary creativity.  Adding to its significance, the House opened the Museum of Repressed Writers in 2021, marking the 100-year anniversary of the Soviet occupation. Supported by Tbilisi - UNESCO World Book Capital 2021, this exhibit, designed by artists Mariam Natroshvili and Detu Jincharadze, features important documents from the SovLab Research Laboratory. The museum is a poignant tribute to the writers who suffered repression, capturing a vital part of Georgia's literary history.  The current director of the House, Natasha Lomouri, appointed in 2011, has played a crucial role in its resurgence. Her leadership has guided the institution to focus on enhancing literary-cultural activities, locally and internationally, with an emphasis on public outreach and education.  The Writer's House aims to popularize Georgian literature, foster creative translation, support various literary processes, and establish literary competitions and awards. It also actively engages with foreign governmental and non-governmental structures and encourages the publication of literary journals.  Beyond its literary importance, the House also offers a delightful gastronomic experience. During the summer months, the lush garden of the House transforms into a restaurant, providing a serene backdrop to enjoy Georgian cuisine.  The Writer's House of Georgia is not just a building but a living monument that encapsulates Georgia's rich literary heritage. From its splendid architecture to its literary activities, the House serves as a vibrant bridge between Georgia's literary past and its evolving present. Whether you're a literary enthusiast, a history buff, or an architecture lover, a visit to the Writer's House is sure to be a memorable part of your Tbilisi experience.   ",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/The%20Writer's%20House%20of%20Georgia.jpg"
 },
