  "Monument": "Art Palace",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Art Palace of Georgia, located in the heart of Tbilisi on Kargareteli Street. Built as a symbol of love by Duke Constantine Petrovich of Oldenburg for Agrippina Japaridze, this architectural masterpiece combines elements of Gothic and Islamic architecture. Previously known as the Georgian State Museum of Theater, Music, Cinema and Choreography, the museum now holds a vast collection of over 300,000 items, detailing the evolution of Georgian scenic design, theatre, cinema, and more. The palace also houses Persian, Russian, and Western European fine art. Don't miss the ancient mask from the town of Vani. Open from Tuesday to Sunday, it's a must-see for art and history lovers!",
  "Medium": "Step into the world of art and culture at the Art Palace of Georgia. This splendid building, located in Tbilisi's Kargareteli Street, was constructed by Duke Constantine Petrovich of Oldenburg as a symbol of his love for Agrippina Japaridze, an event that adds a touch of romance to its history.  Designed by the renowned architect Paul Stern, the palace is a remarkable representation of historicism, showcasing elements of Gothic and Islamic architecture. Its interior design credit also goes to Polish architect Aleksander Rogojski, contributing to its aesthetic appeal.  Originally known as the Georgian State Museum of Theater, Music, Cinema, and Choreography until 2020, the museum now houses a broad range of Georgian cultural objects. With a collection of more than 300,000 items, it offers insights into the development of Georgian theatre, cinema, folklore, opera, and ballet.  Aside from the Georgian Fine Arts collection, the museum holds collections of Russian and Western European fine arts, including works of Russian Silver age World of Art representatives such as Konstantin Korovin, Lev Bakst, Alexander Benua, Alexander Golovin, and Viktor Simov. The collection also showcases Persian Fine Arts, including 19th-century Qajar miniature paintings.  One of the museum's prized possessions is an antique mask excavated in the town of Vani, harking back to the classical era. Open from Tuesday to Sunday, the Art Palace of Georgia is a delightful exploration of Georgia's cultural history and international artistic influences.",
  "Long": "The Art Palace of Georgia, located in Tbilisi, is a treasure trove of Georgian cultural history. It's housed in a building commissioned by Duke Constantine Petrovich of Oldenburg for his beloved Agrippina Japaridze in 1882. This love story brings a romantic allure to the Palace, making it more than just a museum.  Designed by Paul Stern, a well-known architect of the era, the building is an example of historicism and beautifully marries elements of Gothic and Islamic architecture. The interior also boasts the creativity of Polish architect Aleksander Rogojski.  Until 2020, the palace was the Georgian State Museum of Theater, Music, Cinema, and Choreography. Today, as the Art Palace, it stands as a significant repository of Georgian cultural objects. With a staggering collection exceeding 300,000 items, the museum provides an in-depth exploration of the development of various cultural aspects in Georgia - theatre, cinema, circus, folklore, opera, and ballet. It also provides fascinating insights into the lives of notable figures in these fields.  The Georgian Fine Arts collection forms a substantial part of the museum, with about 10,000 exhibits from over 300 Georgian artists. These exhibits paint a comprehensive picture of the evolution of Georgian scenic design, including portraits of theatre actors and directors, and sketches of stage decorations and costumes.  The museum also highlights international artistic influences on Georgia. Its collection of Russian Fine Arts features works of significant Russian painters and artists from the Silver age World of Art, like Konstantin Korovin, Lev Bakst, Alexander Benua, Alexander Golovin, and Viktor Simov.  A Western European Fine Arts collection traces Georgia's long-standing interest in European art, brought back by Georgian nobility during their frequent travels to Europe from the 18th century onwards. Additionally, a collection of Persian Fine Arts exhibits, including 19th-century Qajar miniature paintings and a painting of King Solomon, speak volumes about the Persian influence on Georgian art.  The museum also showcases artifacts from the classical era, including an antique mask excavated in the town of Vani. This mask, along with other exhibits, sheds light on the deep roots and evolution of Georgian culture and art.  The Art Palace of Georgia, open from Tuesday to Sunday, is a captivating blend of architectural beauty, cultural history, and artistic richness. Whether you're an art aficionado, a history enthusiast, or simply a curious traveler, a visit to the Art Palace is sure to leave you enriched and inspired.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Art%20Palace.jpg"
 },
