  "Monument": "Sioni Cathedral",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Sioni Cathedral of the Dormition! A historic jewel of Tbilisi, its name honors Mount Zion in Jerusalem. Founded in the 6th century and rebuilt numerous times, the Cathedral stands as a testament to Georgia's rich history and resilience. Explore the intriguing blend of architectural styles, from its 13th-century structure to 17th-19th-century renovations. Inside, discover mesmerizing murals painted by Russian artist Grigory Gagarin and a stone iconostasis from the 1850s. Don't miss the sacred Grapevine cross, believed to be crafted by Saint Nino herself. Once the main Georgian Orthodox Cathedral, it served as the publication site for the Russian Imperial manifesto on Georgia's annexification. Despite its tumultuous history, it has stood defiantly through the ages and even functioned during Soviet times.",
  "Medium": "Welcome to Tbilisi's captivating Sioni Cathedral of the Dormition, a tribute to Mount Zion in Jerusalem. Located on the scenic Sionis Kucha street, this Georgian Orthodox cathedral has seen a turbulent history since its establishment in the 6th and 7th centuries. Reconstructed many times due to invasions and natural disasters, the cathedral encapsulates Georgia's enduring spirit and rich architectural heritage.  The cathedral you see today is largely a 13th-century construction, with modifications from the 17th to 19th centuries. Its exterior simplicity belies a fascinating interior. Upon entering, you'll be struck by the captivating murals by Russian artist and general Grigory Gagarin, painted between 1850 and 1860. Admire the 1850s stone iconostasis, designed by Gagarin to replace the wooden one destroyed by Persian invaders.  One of the cathedral's treasures is the Grapevine cross, a revered relic tied to Saint Nino, who preached Christianity in Georgia in the 4th century. The Cathedral was also the place where the Russian Imperial manifesto on Georgia's annexation was first announced in 1802, a historic moment that left an indelible mark on Georgian history.  The cathedral remained functional through the Soviet era and even received partial renovations between 1980 and 1983. As you tour this sacred site, soak in the complex history and the stunning beauty that the Sioni Cathedral offers. ",
  "Long": "Welcome to the heart of Tbilisi, the Sioni Cathedral of the Dormition. Nestled in the historic Sionis Kucha and overlooking the Kura River, this Georgian Orthodox cathedral's name echoes Mount Zion in Jerusalem. Constructed in the 6th and 7th centuries, the Cathedral has seen invasions, natural disasters, and significant socio-political changes. Today's structure, based on the 13th-century design, bears the imprints of these turbulent periods, making it a fascinating historical timeline for visitors.  The Sioni Cathedral holds the key to Georgia's rich architectural legacy, spanning centuries. The inscribed cross-in-square design and the polygonal apses on the eastern facade showcase medieval Georgian church architecture. Despite multiple reconstructions, the basic elements remain from King David the Builder's design in 1112, offering glimpses into the architectural brilliance of that era.  Stepping inside, you'll be awestruck by the striking murals composed by Russian artist Grigory Gagarin between 1850 and 1860. These vibrant pieces, along with those by Georgian artist Levan Tsutskiridze from the 1980s, lend the cathedral's interior a unique artistic aura. Gagarin also designed the stone iconostasis dating back to the 1850s, replacing the original wooden one burned during the Persian invasion in 1795.  One of the cathedral's most treasured artifacts is the Grapevine cross, associated with Saint Nino. As per tradition, this Cappadocian woman forged the cross and was instrumental in introducing Christianity to the Caucasus in the 4th century. It's an artifact of spiritual significance that connects modern Georgia with its ancient Christian roots.  The cathedral's history intertwines with significant events in Georgia's past. The Russian Imperial manifesto announcing Georgia's annexation was first made public here in 1802. It was a momentous event, shaping Georgia's future. The cathedral has also served as the main Georgian Orthodox Cathedral and the seat of the Catholicos-Patriarch of All Georgia until the Holy Trinity Cathedral was consecrated in 2004.  The Sioni Cathedral was also the site of various restorations, including the cupola and vaults by the Metropolitan of Tbilisi, Elise Saginashvili, in the 17th century. It even continued functioning throughout the Soviet era, with partial renovations undertaken between 1980 and 1983.  Near the cathedral, within the courtyard, a three-story bell tower stands tall. This structure, dating from the 1425 reconstruction by King Alexander I and restored in 1939 after being largely destroyed by Persian Shah Agha Mohammad Khan Qajar in 1795, is another architectural marvel.  The Sioni Cathedral's journey is a remarkable narrative of resilience, strength, and enduring faith. As you explore its hallowed grounds, you're not just visiting a religious structure; you're stepping into a living testament of Georgian history, culture, and spirituality.    ",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Sioni%20Cathedral.jpg"
 },
