  "Monument": "The Chronicle of Georgia",
  "Short": "The Chronicle of Georgia, a monument located near the Tbilisi Sea, is a testament to Georgia's rich history. Created by Zurab Tsereteli in 1985, it is an unfinished masterpiece composed of 16 towering pillars. The monument's top half showcases Georgian kings, queens, and heroes, while the bottom half narrates tales from Christ's life. You'll also see St. Nino's grapevine cross and a chapel. The monument provides a stunning overview of Tbilisi and is near the Tbilisi Sea, a popular local attraction. Though it's less frequented by tourists due to Tbilisi's myriad of attractions, it offers an unparalleled insight into Georgia's past.",
  "Medium": "Welcome to the Chronicle of Georgia, a colossal monument erected near the Tbilisi Sea that stands as a testament to Georgia's vibrant history and strong religious influences. This masterpiece was created by Zurab Tsereteli, a Georgian-Russian sculptor, in 1985 but was never fully completed due to funding issues following the collapse of the Soviet Union and the Russo Georgian War.  The monument features 16 pillars standing between 30 to 35 meters tall. The upper halves depict Georgian royalty and heroic figures, while the lower halves depict stories from the life of Christ. You'll also find the revered grapevine cross of St. Nino, the woman who brought Christianity to Georgia, and a chapel.  This monument tells the tale of Georgian history, from the advent of pottery-making technology, agriculture, and wine brewing to the Christian era and the subsequent cultural shifts. It marks Georgia's annexation by Russia in 1783 and its incorporation into the Soviet Union in 1936.  The monument's location on a large hill provides a breathtaking view of Tbilisi, making it an intriguing spot for tourists despite being lesser-known due to the city's diverse attractions. In the vicinity, you will also find the Tbilisi Sea, an artificial lake that is a hit among the locals.  Despite its unfinished state, the Chronicle of Georgia serves as a tangible chronicle of Georgia's history and culture, immortalizing the nation's journey over centuries.",
  "Long": "Welcome to the Chronicle of Georgia, an imposing monument proudly standing near the Tbilisi Sea. This structure serves as an immense stone tapestry, detailing the rich tapestry of Georgia's history and religious influences. Masterminded by renowned Georgian-Russian sculptor Zurab Tsereteli in 1985, it remains an unfinished work of art. Its construction was halted in the early 1990s due to the collapse of the Soviet Union and the Russo Georgian War.  Dominating the landscape, the monument features 16 colossal pillars standing between 30 to 35 meters tall. The upper halves immortalize Georgian kings, queens, and heroes, while the lower halves weave tales from the life of Christ into stone. Additionally, you'll find a chapel and the grapevine cross of St. Nino, the woman who introduced Christianity to Georgia. Her symbol, the grapevine cross, is seen here in honor of her monumental influence.  The monument serves as a visual narration of the profound historical events that shaped Georgia. It commemorates the early eras when humans first settled in Georgia, evolving slowly since the Paleolithic Era. It pays homage to the advent of the agricultural revolution, marking the introduction of domesticated plants and agriculture that proved pivotal in the evolution of Georgian culture.  The Chronicle of Georgia also highlights Georgia's pottery-making and wine-brewing prowess, which played a critical role in the nation's cultural development. It records Georgia's annexation by Russia in 1783 and its incorporation into the Soviet Union in 1936, which led to the funding of this monument by Soviet funds.  Situated on a large hill, the Chronicle of Georgia provides an unparalleled panoramic view of Tbilisi. It is an excellent spot for tourists to capture the beauty of the city. Despite being overshadowed by Tbilisi's diverse array of attractions, it's an intriguing location that provides an insight into the nation's past and cultural heritage.  Just a stone's throw away from the monument, you'll find the Tbilisi Sea, an artificial lake built in 1953 that serves as a popular hangout for the locals. Although it's an artificial lake, its vast expanse and depth create the illusion of a sea. Its proximity to the monument makes the location all the more enticing for visitors looking to immerse themselves in Georgia's cultural and natural splendors.  Zurab Tsereteli, the mastermind behind this monument, has made substantial contributions to the art world with his monumental sculptures and architectural designs. His work on the Chronicle of Georgia coincides with his construction of the Friendship Forever in Moscow's Tishinskaya square, signifying the deep-rooted friendship between Russia and Georgia.  Despite its unfinished state, the Chronicle of Georgia stands as an impressive testament to Georgia's rich history, cultural development, and religious influence. It is a tangible chronicle that offers an unparalleled insight into Georgia's journey through the centuries. For those visiting Tbilisi, it presents a unique opportunity to connect with the nation's past and appreciate its cultural evolution.",
