  "Monument": "Ethnography Museum",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Giorgi Chitaia Open Air Museum of Ethnography in Tbilisi, Georgia. This museum, founded by ethnographer Giorgi Chitaia in 1966, offers a splendid display of folk architecture and craftwork from across the country. Spanning 52 hectares, the museum houses 70 buildings and over 8,000 items, each telling a unique story of Georgia's rich cultural heritage. Experience the eastern Georgian darbazi-type stone houses, western Georgian wooden houses with gable roofs, traditional watchtowers, wineries, water mills, and a collection of traditional household articles. The museum also hosts the annual Art-Gene folk culture festival, providing a vibrant showcase of Georgian folk art and music.",
  "Medium": "Welcome to the Giorgi Chitaia Open Air Museum of Ethnography, a unique museum showcasing the diverse architectural and cultural heritage of Georgia. Established in 1966 by Giorgi Chitaia, a renowned Georgian ethnographer, this museum is an expansive open-air collection of folk architecture and craftwork that represents different regions of the country.  The museum sprawls over 52 hectares of land, organized into eleven zones, with about 70 buildings relocated from various Georgian territories. It offers an immersive experience as you walk through eastern Georgia's darbazi-type and flat-roofed stone houses, and explore openwork wooden houses with straw or board gable roofs from western Georgia. You'll find watchtowers from mountainous provinces like Khevsureti, Pshavi, and Svaneti, along with Megrelian and Imeretian maize storages, Kakhetian wineries (marani), and Kartlian water mills.  Beyond architecture, the museum houses over 8,000 items reflecting Georgia's cultural past. Discover traditional distaffs, knitting-frames, chums, clothes, carpets, pottery, furniture, and more. Notably, it features an early Christian Sioni basilica from Tianeti and a 6th-7th century familial burial vault with sarcophagus, offering glimpses into Georgia's spiritual history.  Since 2004, the museum has been the proud host of the annual summertime Art-Gene folk culture festival, founded and managed by Georgian rock musician and folk enthusiast Zaza Korinteli. This festival adds a vibrant touch to the museum, promoting traditional Georgian arts, music, and crafts.",
  "Long": "Welcome to the Giorgi Chitaia Open Air Museum of Ethnography, a unique open-air museum located west to Turtle Lake on a hill overlooking the Vake district, Tbilisi. Founded by ethnographer Giorgi Chitaia in 1966, the museum is a homage to Georgia's rich cultural heritage, capturing the essence of the nation's folk architecture and craftwork. The museum is named after its founder and has been managed as part of the Georgian National Museum since 2004.  Occupying 52 hectares of land, the museum features eleven zones that showcase the diverse regional architecture and culture of Georgia. Around 70 buildings have been carefully moved here from all the main territorial subdivisions of Georgia, transforming the museum into a historic village. The structures range from traditional darbazi-type and flat-roofed stone houses of eastern Georgia to openwork wooden houses with gable roofs of straw or boards from western Georgia.  You'll see watchtowers from the mountainous provinces of Khevsureti, Pshavi, and Svaneti, each with their distinct architectural characteristics. The museum also houses Megrelian and Imeretian wattle maize storages, Kakhetian wineries (marani), and Kartlian water mills, providing insights into Georgia's age-old agricultural practices and wine-making traditions.  Apart from the architectural marvels, the museum houses over 8,000 artifacts including traditional household articles, clothes, carpets, pottery, furniture, and more. Witness the intricacy of Georgian craftwork through items like distaffs and knitting-frames, as well as a wide variety of chums. These items narrate the story of Georgia's past and reflect the unique traditions and practices that have shaped its identity.  The museum is also home to an early Christian Sioni basilica from Tianeti and a 6th-7th century familial burial vault with sarcophagus, allowing visitors to delve deeper into Georgia's spiritual history. These structures offer valuable insights into the country's early Christian era and the architectural styles prevalent during that time.  The museum's vibrancy is further accentuated by the annual summertime Art-Gene folk culture festival. Since 2004, the museum has been hosting this festival, founded and managed by the Georgian rock musician and folk enthusiast Zaza Korinteli (Zumba). The festival brings together artists, musicians, and craftsmen from across Georgia, promoting the country's traditional art forms, music, and crafts. It provides a platform for cultural exchange and preservation of Georgia's folk heritage, adding to the overall appeal of the museum.  In a nutshell, the Giorgi Chitaia Open Air Museum of Ethnography is more than just a museum. It's an immersive cultural experience that transports you through the various epochs of Georgia's history. Whether you're an architecture enthusiast, a history buff, or a curious traveler, this museum offers a fascinating exploration of Georgia's rich cultural tapestry.   ",
