  "Monument": "Fine Art Museum of Georgia",
  "Short": "Welcome to the Fine Art Museum of Georgia, an artistic treasure house showcasing an array of Georgian, Oriental, Russian, and European art. The museum, founded in 1920 and named after art historian Shalva Amiranashvili, harbors over 140,000 art pieces. Marvel at the Georgian art collection, illustrating the nation's artistic evolution from ancient times to present. Don't miss the Oriental section, one of the largest in post-Soviet countries, spotlighting the fine art of the Persian Qajar era. Make sure to visit special exhibitions frequently held to display artworks from diverse collections.",
  "Medium": "Immerse yourself in the artistic brilliance of Georgia at the Fine Art Museum of Georgia, alternatively known as Shalva Amiranashvili Museum of Fine Arts. Founded in 1920, the museum holds an esteemed position in Georgia's cultural landscape, boasting around 140,000 pieces of Georgian, Oriental, Russian, and European art.  Established as the National Art Gallery through the dedicated efforts of Western-educated Georgian artists, the museum was transformed into the Central Museum of Fine Arts in 1923. The museum has undergone various transformations, eventually becoming the Art Museum of Georgia in 1950 and being incorporated into the Georgian National Museum in 2004.  The museum is named after the prominent Georgian art historian Shalva Amiranashvili, who headed the museum for over thirty years and played a significant role in shaping its collection. Housed in a neoclassical building from 1838 that once served as a theological seminary, the museum provides a unique blend of historical architecture and vibrant artistic heritage.  Explore the extensive collection of Georgian art, a journey through the country's rich artistic tradition from ancient times to the present. Also, experience the grandeur of Persian fine arts in the Oriental section, particularly the Qajar art. This collection includes exquisite miniatures of Persian court artists, capturing images of court beauties, shahs, and noblemen. Don't miss the museum's temporary exhibitions that bring in art pieces from other collections in the country and abroad.",
  "Long": "Welcome to the Fine Art Museum of Georgia, an artistic gem in the heart of Tbilisi. Known as the Shalva Amiranashvili Museum of Fine Arts, this museum is home to a wide-ranging collection of Georgian, Oriental, Russian, and European art. Established in 1920, the museum's expansive collection of approximately 140,000 pieces makes it one of Georgia's leading art institutions.  The museum was initially launched as the National Art Gallery by a group of Western-educated Georgian artists. It subsequently evolved into the Central Museum of Fine Arts in 1923. The museum was relocated to the old city's center in 1932, on the site of the 13th-century Metekhi church. It officially became the Art Museum of Georgia in 1950 when it moved into its current neoclassical building, constructed in 1838 as a theological seminary during the Imperial Russian period.  Shalva Amiranashvili, a celebrated Georgian art historian, played a crucial role in shaping the museum's collection. His efforts over a tenure of more than thirty years brought many significant pieces to the museum, meriting the institution to be named after him. In 2004, the museum was incorporated into the Georgian National Museum, marking another key milestone in its history.  As you explore the museum, you'll encounter a vast array of Georgian art illustrating the nation's artistic culture's evolution from ancient times to the present. This collection provides an extraordinary insight into the country's rich artistic tradition, making it a vital part of the museum.  The Oriental section is another highlight, ranking among the largest in the post-Soviet countries. The collection showcases the brilliance of Persian fine arts, particularly from the Qajar era. It includes several miniatures by Persian court artists, displaying images of court beauties and portraits of shahs and noblemen. These artworks present a beautiful reflection of the Persian court's life and its artistic preferences.  The museum's Russian and European collections add further depth to the artistic journey, presenting a diverse range of art styles and periods. The story of the stolen and then returned 16th-century painting The Procuress by Lucas Cranach the Elder adds a layer of intrigue and history to the collection.  Regularly, the museum hosts temporary exhibitions, featuring works from different collections within the country and from abroad. These exhibitions bring fresh perspectives and narratives to the museum, ensuring there's always something new for the visitors.  The Art Museum of Georgia offers a unique journey into the artistic heritage of Georgia and beyond. Its diverse collections reflect various cultural influences and historical periods, making it a must-visit for art lovers and history enthusiasts. Whether it's your first visit or a return trip, the museum continually offers new insights into the world of art.",
