  "Monument": "Kashveti Church of St. George",
  "Short": "Welcome to the stunning Kashveti Church of St. George! A masterful blend of Georgian, Italian, and German influences, this Georgian Orthodox Church stands across the Parliament building in the heart of Tbilisi. Constructed from 1904 to 1910, its architecture echoes the medieval Samtavisi Cathedral. Breathtaking frescoes by celebrated Georgian artist Lado Gudiashvili adorn the interior, illustrating Christian stories with ancient encaustic techniques. A site of deep historical and religious significance, Kashveti takes its name from an old legend featuring the 6th-century monk, David of Gareja, who proved his innocence against false accusations by causing a woman to give birth to a stone. This story, reflected in the church's name, weaves faith, history, and miracles together, attracting believers and tourists alike.",
  "Medium": "Welcome to the magnificent Kashveti Church of St. George, an architectural jewel standing proudly in central Tbilisi, opposite the Parliament building. Kashveti's design, crafted by the architect Leopold Bilfeldt, is inspired by the medieval Samtavisi Cathedral, culminating in a harmonious blend of Italian marble and carvings copied from various ancient churches in Georgia.  The church was built between 1904 and 1910, replacing a previous structure from 1753 that had fallen into disrepair. Notably, the construction was saved from Soviet destruction in the 1920s thanks to Neophyte Agladze, a local master stone carver who contributed to Kashveti's ornate design.  Upon entering, your eyes will be captivated by the exquisitely painted frescoes created by Lado Gudiashvili, one of Georgia's most influential painters. His work, a testament to the encaustic painting method, features timeless Christian narratives and has survived the test of time.  The church is deeply rooted in Georgian Christianity. Its name, kashveti, stems from an intriguing tale about the 6th-century monk David of Gareja, a figure in the group of the Thirteen Assyrian Fathers. Falsely accused of impregnating a woman, David prophesied she would give birth to a stone in his defense, which she indeed did. This miracle birth gave the church its name and enhances its allure as a symbol of faith, history, and miracles.  Long text (500 words):  Welcome to the inspiring Kashveti Church of St. George, an embodiment of Georgian Orthodox tradition and artistic splendor. Sitting opposite the Parliament building on Tbilisi's bustling Rustavel",
  "Long": "Welcome to the inspiring Kashveti Church of St. George, an embodiment of Georgian Orthodox tradition and artistic splendor. Sitting opposite the Parliament building on Tbilisi's bustling Rustaveli Avenue, Kashveti's majestic silhouette narrates stories of faith, resilience, and artistry.  Constructed between 1904 and 1910, this church stands on hallowed ground. Previous structures date back to the 6th century, each one testament to the enduring spirit of Georgian Christianity. Kashveti replaced a deteriorating church from 1753, with contributions from the Georgian nobility and bourgeoisie funding the project. Architect Leopold Bilfeldt's design drew inspiration from the medieval Samtavisi Cathedral, combining it with Italian marble and diverse Georgian carvings to create a harmonious blend of architectural styles.  Though the church faced demolition during the anti-religious Soviet regime in the 1920s, it was saved through the quick thinking of Neophyte Agladze. As a master stone carver, Agladze's passion for his work led him to rally support and prevent the church's destruction, allowing Kashveti to stand as a beacon of faith even today.  Kashveti's interior is as remarkable as its history. The church's walls are adorned with enchanting frescoes painted by Lado Gudiashvili, a leading figure in Georgian art. Utilizing the ancient and robust encaustic painting method, Gudiashvili breathed life into Christian narratives, creating an immersive and spiritual experience for all visitors.  At the heart of Kashveti's history is the legend of David of Gareja, one of the Thirteen Assyrian Fathers who evangelized Georgia in the 6th century. Falsely accused of impregnating a woman, David declared that she would birth a stone to prove his innocence. Miraculously, this prophecy came to pass, resulting in the church's name kashveti, which translates to birth of a stone. This miraculous event not only reinforced the sanctity of the site but also symbolized the unwavering resilience and faith of the Georgian people.  Today, Kashveti Church stands as an iconic symbol of Georgia's rich religious history, architectural splendor, and enduring faith. Its remarkable blend of design influences, stunning frescoes, and legendary origins make it a must-visit destination for any visitor to Tbilisi. Whether you are a history buff, an art enthusiast, or a spiritual seeker, the Kashveti Church of St. George promises an unforgettable experience.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Kashveti%20Church%20of%20St.%20George.jpg"
 },
