  "Monument": "Meidan District",
  "Short": "Welcome to Meidan, the beating heart of Old Tbilisi, bustling with history and life. Explore characteristic architecture, take a relaxing dip in sulfur baths, marvel at the blue-mosaic mosque, and experience the tranquility of Leghvtakhevi Waterfall. From Meidan, gaze upon the Metekhi Temple and Narikala Fortress. Stop by the numerous cafes and shops, taste traditional Georgian dishes, and shop for items inspired by Georgian culture. Don't miss the St. George Armenian Cathedral, home to Sayat-Nova's tomb, and the nearby Botanical Garden.",
  "Medium": "Step into Meidan, a vibrant district in Old Tbilisi brimming with history, art, and culture. This district offers a distinctive architectural aesthetic, from sulfur baths to a beautifully decorated blue-mosaic mosque, not to mention the serene Leghvtakhevi Waterfall. From this central hub, you can witness the majestic Metekhi Temple and Narikala Fortress. Immerse yourself in local culture by visiting the numerous cafes, restaurants, and shops offering traditional Georgian cuisine and items inspired by Georgian art and history. Be sure to visit the St. George Armenian Cathedral, where the famous poet Sayat-Nova is buried. Close by is the captivating Botanical Garden. Once a medieval trading center known as the walk of life, Meidan continues to pulse with the vibrant rhythm of Tbilisi's life and culture.",
  "Long": "Venture into the heart of Meidan, a district at the core of Old Tbilisi, steeped in history and rich in cultural expressions. As you stroll around, you'll encounter an eclectic mix of architecture, from traditional structures to the sulfur baths, and a striking mosque adorned with a blue mosaic. Listen closely, and you might hear the tranquil sound of the Leghvtakhevi Waterfall nearby. From this hub, you have a clear view of the majestic Metekhi Temple and the Narikala Fortress standing proudly over Tbilisi.  Meidan has a storied past, once a critical trading center in medieval Tbilisi, known as the walk of life. The renowned scholar Vakhushti Batonishvili referred to it as the ‚ÄúKing Meidan‚Äù and ‚ÄúMeidan of prison.‚Äù Today, it continues to serve as a key gathering place, keeping its vibrant energy alive.  Experience the local flavor by visiting the bustling cafes and restaurants, where you can sample a myriad of delicious Georgian dishes. As you explore the square, you'll find shops filled with items, drinks, carpets, and antiques crafted on Georgian motives, offering a tangible piece of this unique culture.  Don't miss the St. George Armenian Cathedral, home to the tomb of the famous poet Sayat-Nova, a must-see for any literary enthusiast. And just a short walk away lies the splendid Botanical Garden, an oasis of tranquility and natural beauty within the city's hustle and bustle.  Indeed, Meidan is more than a district; it's a living testament to Tbilisi's past and present, serving as a vibrant walk of life that continues to enchant residents and visitors alike. As you traverse its paths, you're not merely sightseeing; you're participating in a centuries-old narrative that's still unfolding.",
