  "Monument": "House of Melik-Azaryants",
  "Short": "Visit the House of Melik-Azaryants, an iconic monument on Tbilisi's central Rustaveli Avenue. This stunning edifice, built in the Art Nouveau style, represents an architectural gem from the early 20th century. Marvel at the stone-carved garlands, Czech sculptural reliefs, and traditional Tbilisian wooden balconies adorning the building. This house, built on a former landfill, was a progressive multipurpose complex of its time, boasting hotel rooms, shops, a photo salon, preschool, cinema, and an art gallery. The House of Melik-Azaryants tells a poignant tale of the owner's loss, reflected in its ascetic appearance, tear-shaped windows, and funeral wreaths.",
  "Medium": "Immerse yourself in the compelling history of the House of Melik-Azaryants, an iconic monument steeped in history and art, nestled within Tbilisi's Rustaveli Avenue. Built by a wealthy Armenian merchant, Alexander Melik-Azaryants, in the Art Nouveau style from 1912-1915, the house stands as an embodiment of modernist architecture of that era.  Admire its fascinating exterior featuring intricate stone-carved garlands, Czech sculptural reliefs, and traditional Tbilisian wooden balconies. The house holds the distinction of being Europe and Russia's first modern-style, multifunctional complex, accommodating hotel rooms, shops, a photo salon, preschool, cinema, and an art gallery. The house's remarkable features included electricity, heating, and running water, all novel inclusions at that time.  The House of Melik-Azaryants carries a melancholic tale of loss, mirrored in its ascetic appearance, tear-shaped windows, and funeral wreaths ‚Äî a father's tribute to his daughter who passed away during its construction.",
  "Long": "Welcome to the House of Melik-Azaryants, a historical monument of significant importance on Rustaveli Avenue, Tbilisi. This exceptional architectural gem was constructed by a wealthy Armenian merchant, Alexander Melik-Azaryants, in the Art Nouveau style between 1912-1915, reflecting Tbilisi's prevalent modernist architecture.  From its ornate stone-carved garlands and Czech sculptural reliefs that grace the facade, to the traditional Tbilisian wooden balconies that embellish the back, the house is an embodiment of textural contrast. The tale of its construction is as fascinating as its architecture. The merchant, initially outraged at the prospect of building on a landfill, eventually accepted the mayor's offer, leading to the creation of this unique edifice.  Notably, the house was the first multifunctional, modern-style building in all of Europe and Russia at the time. Housing hotel rooms, shops, a photo salon, preschool, cinema, art gallery, and a beautiful garden, it was a testament to innovative urban planning. The inclusion of amenities such as electricity, heating, and running water was a significant leap in the era's architectural standards.  However, the house also carries a sorrowful tale of a grieving father. Alexander Melik-Azaryants's daughter tragically passed away before its completion, leading him to dedicate the building to her memory. The house's sad and ascetic appearance, epitomized by teardrop windows and funeral wreaths, is a moving tribute to his loss.  During the Soviet Era, Azaryants‚Äôs property, including the house, was nationalized. He died in poverty, leaving behind this unique dwelling as his lasting legacy. Despite facing demolition threats several times, the house stands today as a cherished monument of Tbilisi's cultural heritage.  The House of Melik-Azaryants is not just a building; it is a symbol of enduring love, resilience, and innovation. Its architectural splendor and poignant history make it a must-visit site for any visitor to Tbilisi.",
