  "Monument": "Assumption Church of Metekhi",
  "Short": "The Virgin Mary Assumption Church of Metekhi, also known as Metekhi Church, is a key Georgian Orthodox Christian site in Tbilisi, dating back to the 13th century. Perched on the Metekhi Cliff, the church offers a breathtaking view of the old town across the Kura river. Its unique architecture, with three convex apses and a dome held internally by four pillars, make it a significant historical monument. The church's stone walls are adorned with intricate rock carvings, a testimony to Georgia's Golden Age. Metekhi also has a tragic history, notably the event of 1226, when around 100,000 citizens were executed for refusing to step on holy icons. Today, the church continues to be a place of worship and a fascinating historical site for tourists.",
  "Medium": "The Virgin Mary Assumption Church of Metekhi, located on a cliff overlooking the Kura river, is a stunning example of Georgian architectural grandeur, dating back to the 13th century. According to oral tradition, its origins could trace back to as early as the 5th century, built by the King Vakhtang I Gorgasali. However, most of its current structure was constructed under the reign of King Demetrius II, between 1278 and 1289 AD.  The church uniquely blends into the natural landscape, constructed to appear as an extension of the cliff. With three convex apses and a dome supported internally by four pillars, Metekhi's design differs from most churches of the time, making it a unique monument. The walls of the church are decorated with Georgian rock carvings, an artistic element characteristic of the Golden Age of 11th-12th centuries.  A tragic event in 1226 has been immortalized in the church's history. The Kwarazm-shah, Jalal ad-Din, ordered Tbilisi's citizens to step on religious icons or face execution. About 100,000 citizens who refused to desecrate their faith were executed, their heads floating down the Mtkvari River.  During the 17th century, the church underwent significant restorations due to damage from lightning. In the Soviet era, the church was used as a museum, theater, and even a prison, with prisoner names etched into its facade. It returned to its sacred function in 1988 and has since been a beacon of faith, history, and culture.",
  "Long": "Standing on the edge of the Metekhi Cliff, overlooking the old town of Tbilisi, lies the impressive structure of The Virgin Mary Assumption Church of Metekhi, an integral part of Georgia's rich history. Known locally as Metekhi Church, this Georgian Orthodox Christian place of worship has roots dating back to the 13th century, with oral tradition hinting at an even earlier foundation in the 5th century by the King Vakhtang I Gorgasali. Despite these early roots, the bulk of its current structure was erected under the rule of King Demetrius II between 1278 and 1289 AD.  An exquisite example of Georgian architecture, Metekhi Church seamlessly blends with its natural surroundings, designed to look like an extension of the cliff it sits upon. Its unique architectural style boasts three convex apses and a dome, supported internally by four pillars, standing in contrast to the typical two-pillar design of the 11th century. These structural elements contribute to Metekhi's uniqueness and the invaluable insights it provides into historical architectural trends.  The exterior walls, crafted from hewn quadras, have been adorned with traditional Georgian rock carvings, exuding a distinct charm associated with the Golden Age of 11th-12th centuries. The eastern facade features the best-preserved carvings, offering an intricate display of rhombic rosettes and convex architraves. While no original murals have survived inside, various icons, such as the 100000 martyrs, narrate stories of the past.  One of the most tragic events connected to the church took place in 1226 when the town was seized by troops led by Kwarazm-shah, Jalal ad-Din. He presented an appalling ultimatum to Tbilisi's inhabitants: step on religious icons from Sioni Church, which were laid on the Metekhi Bridge, or face beheading. Defying this sacrilegious command, about 100,000 citizens were executed, their heads sent floating down the Mtkvari River, a grim reminder of the price paid for steadfast faith.  Over the centuries, Metekhi Church has weathered a variety of transformations. In the 17th century, after a lightning strike, significant restoration work was undertaken. In the 18th century, changes were made, including the addition of a southern entrance and the substitution of original hewn quadras with bricks on the southern facade.  During the Soviet era, the church was repurposed several times. It served as a prison during the early Soviet era, with prisoners leaving their mark by scratching their names into the church's facade. It was then transformed into a depository for the National Museum of Art's collections and later served as a youth theater in the 1970s.  Despite the turbulent times and multiple threats of demolition, Metekhi Church survived and was reinstated as a place of worship in 1988. Today, this remarkable monument stands as a testament to Georgia's rich history, a symbol of resilient faith, and a captivating attraction for both locals and tourists alike, offering a unique glimpse into the country's religious, cultural, and architectural heritage.",
  "Image": "https://www.wagnerproducciones.com/travelmeit/monumentos_tbilisi/Assumption%20Church%20of%20Metekhi.jpg"
 },
