  "Monument": "Animated Puppet Museum",
  "Short": "Discover a whimsical world of art and tradition at the Animated Puppet Museum in Tbilisi. Home to over three thousand exhibits, including dolls in traditional Georgian attire, the museum reflects a blend of creativity, culture, and craftsmanship. Founded in the 1930s by Tamar Tumanishvili, a children's author and teacher, the museum boasts an eclectic mix of dolls, mechanical toys, and unique embroideries from 40 different countries. These exhibits are the result of eight decades of dedication from artists, collectors, and toy factories alike. Experience the captivating tales of Georgian folklore through these inanimate yet expressive characters. Situated at Agmashenebeli Avenue 103, the museum is open every day from 10:00 to 18:00, except Mondays.",
  "Medium": "Venture into a world of artistry and imagination at the Animated Puppet Museum in Tbilisi, Georgia. With over three thousand exhibits, the museum provides a glimpse into the cultural diversity of the world and Georgian traditions, portrayed through dolls and toys. It all began in the 1930s when Tamar Tumanishvili, a renowned children's author and teacher, envisioned a museum that celebrated the craft of puppet-making and toy creation.  The museum's collection is an assemblage of decades of diligent work from a multitude of contributors. Artists, ethnographers, travelers, hobbyists, constructor-inventors, and private collectors have all had a hand in shaping this museum. Toy factories, partnering with various Georgian and foreign artists, have striven to create the many distinctive exhibits you see today.  What does the Animated Puppet Museum offer? You'll find original samples from 40 countries, preserving a multitude of cultures and traditions within its walls. The collection includes 19th and 20th-century musical and mechanical toys, dolls clad in traditional attire, and figures from Georgian fairy tales, all the way to flamenco dancers, Indian chiefs, and Japanese ladies. Additionally, the museum showcases an assortment of fine and applied artworks, and a unique collection of embroidery.  The Animated Puppet Museum, located at Agmashenebeli Avenue 103, is a must-visit attraction in Tbilisi. Visitors are welcome every day from 10:00 to 18:00, excluding Mondays.",
  "Long": "Step into a universe brimming with creativity, culture, and imagination at Tbilisi's Animated Puppet Museum. This unique cultural landmark boasts over three thousand exhibits, transporting you into the heart of Georgian traditions and global artistry through its extensive collection of dolls and toys.  The foundation of the museum dates back to the 1930s. Tamar Tumanishvili, an acclaimed children's author and teacher, envisioned a haven for toy enthusiasts and lovers of folk culture. She brought her vision to life in 1937, opening the museum in Tbilisi with a rich collection of dolls and toys.  Over the subsequent eight decades, the museum evolved, steadily filling its shelves with treasures. An assortment of contributors, from artists and ethnographers to travelers and hobbyists, have poured their passion and skills into the museum. They worked alongside constructor-inventors and private collectors to curate a unique blend of exhibits. Toy factories, too, played a pivotal role, collaborating with numerous Georgian and foreign artists to breathe life into the models displayed.  What fascinating artifacts can you expect to see within the museum's walls? The Animated Puppet Museum houses an impressive collection of original items from 40 different countries, thereby encapsulating a myriad of cultures and traditions. This includes a wide array of 19th and 20th-century musical and mechanical toys, each an exquisite testament to the craftsmanship of their era.  The dolls, in particular, paint a vivid picture of cultural diversity. From dolls dressed in traditional Georgian attire known as Chikhtikopi, flamenco dancers capturing the fiery spirit of Spanish dance, Indian chiefs embodying the rich heritage of Native American tribes, to elegant Japanese ladies representing the delicate grace of Japanese culture, these inanimate figures tell tales of distant lands and times.  The museum also features characters from Georgian fairy tales, allowing visitors to immerse themselves in local folklore. These well-loved characters, frozen in time yet brimming with stories, form an integral part of the museum's allure.  In addition to these enchanting figures, the museum exhibits a vast collection of fine and applied artworks. This includes a unique collection of embroidery, demonstrating the intricate artistry and diligence of textile artists over the years.  Situated at Agmashenebeli Avenue 103, the Animated Puppet Museum is a treasure trove of artistic expressions and a vivid testament to the universal love for dolls and toys. It operates every day from 10:00 to 18:00, except Mondays.  Visiting the Animated Puppet Museum is not merely a tour; it's an adventure. It's an exploration of history, culture, and creativity through the eyes of inanimate yet expressive characters. Whether you're an art aficionado, a history buff, or simply curious, the museum promises an unforgettable journey into the fascinating world of animated puppets.",
