  "Medium": "The Tbilisi Sea, a tranquil oasis, sits in the northeast of Georgia's bustling capital city. Built in 1951 during the Soviet Union era, this artificial reservoir was originally designed to serve the irrigation system but has since transformed into a recreational hotspot. The water body, 8.75km long and 1.85km wide, perches 630-650m above sea level. It offers visitors opportunities to engage in water sports, take boat trips, or simply enjoy a relaxing swim.  A must-visit site is the Chronicles of Georgia, a monument by Zurab Tsereteli located at one end of the Tbilisi Sea. Sculpted in stone and bronze, it illustrates significant Georgian historical and religious events and vivid scenes from famous literary works. It's a stunning artistic representation of Georgia's rich heritage and a great spot for photographs.  Tucked behind the monuments, you will find the Holy Mother of God Church. Its location on a hill provides visitors with a breathtaking view of the Tbilisi Sea and an expansive panorama of Tbilisi's diverse districts. This spot offers a unique blend of spirituality and scenic beauty that's not to be missed.  On the shores of the Tbilisi Sea, you'll find Gino Paradise, a top-rated water park in Eastern Europe. This park features 9 pools, multiple slides, a wellness center, sports activities, and dining facilities. Gino Paradise offers an ideal escape from the city's hustle and bustle, providing fun and relaxation for adults and children alike.",
