  "Long": "Tucked away on the outskirts of Tbilisi, Georgia's bustling capital city, lies the tranquil haven of Turtle Lake. Known in Georgian as Kus Tba, the lake is situated on the northern slope of the Mtatsminda ridge, some 686.7 meters above sea level. While modest in size with a surface area of 0.034 km, Turtle Lake offers visitors a unique blend of natural beauty, recreational activities, and cultural exploration.  The lake was created by exotectonics, primarily as a result of landslide rocks. Water from the Varaziskhevi river, rain, and groundwater feeds into the lake. Despite its fish scarcity, Turtle Lake teems with life. It derives its name from the numerous turtles that inhabit its waters.  An array of sports and recreational facilities border the lake. Here, the beach, mini-football stadium, children's playground, and boating facilities provide ample opportunity for visitors of all ages to engage in fun and relaxing activities. In summer, the lake comes alive with locals and tourists flocking to the beach and the numerous open-air cafes and bars. The professional concert stage with a pontoon becomes a vibrant hub for various events, adding a cultural element to the leisurely atmosphere.  One of the lake's main attractions is the open-air ethnographic museum located on its northern slope. This unique display presents a miniature model of Georgia, showcasing the country's diverse culture, architecture, and geography. It's a fantastic opportunity for visitors to familiarize themselves with Georgian traditions and lifestyle without having to traverse the entire country.  Access to Turtle Lake was significantly improved in 2016 with the inauguration of an updated ropeway. The gondolas, which can comfortably accommodate 10-12 people, offer an effortless and scenic 6-minute ride from Ilia Chavchavadze Avenue to the lake. Notably, the gondolas and stations are designed to cater to individuals with disabilities, ensuring the lake's attractions are accessible to 